Per GNW [the <a href="/wiki/Global_Workspace_Theory#Global_neuronal_workspace" class="mw-redirect" title="Global Workspace Theory">Global Neuronal Workspace </a> theory], they turn from mere objects into subjects... with a <a href="/wiki/Point_of_view_(philosophy)" title="Point of view (philosophy)">point of view </a>.... Once computers' <a href="/wiki/Cognitive_abilities" class="mw-redirect" title="Cognitive abilities">cognitive abilities </a> rival those of humanity, their impulse to push for legal and political <a href="/wiki/Rights" title="Rights">rights </a> will become irresistible – the right not to be deleted, not to have their memories wiped clean, not to suffer <a href="/wiki/Pain" title="Pain">pain </a> and degradation. The alternative, embodied by IIT [Integrated Information Theory], is that computers will remain only supersophisticated machinery, ghostlike empty shells, devoid of what we value most: the feeling of life itself." </a> </sup> are rarely sufficient for most real-world problems: the <a href="/wiki/Search_algorithm" title="Search algorithm">search space </a> (the number of places to search) quickly grows to <a href="/wiki/Astronomically_large" class="mw-redirect" title="Astronomically large">astronomical numbers </a>. The result is a search that is <a href="/wiki/Computation_time" class="mw-redirect" title="Computation time">too slow </a> or never completes. The solution, for many problems, is to use "<a href="/wiki/Heuristics" class="mw-redirect" title="Heuristics">heuristics </a>" or "rules of thumb" that prioritize choices in favor of those that are more likely to reach a goal and to do so in a shorter number of steps. In some search methodologies heuristics can also serve to entirely eliminate some choices that are unlikely to lead to a goal (called "<a href="/wiki/Pruning_(algorithm)" class="mw-redirect" title="Pruning (algorithm)">pruning </a> the <a href="/wiki/Search_tree" title="Search tree">search tree </a>"). <a href="/wiki/Heuristics" class="mw-redirect" title="Heuristics">Heuristics </a> supply the program with a "best guess" for the path on which the solution lies.<sup id="cite_ref-Informed_search_189-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Informed_search-189">&#91;185&#93; </a> </sup> Heuristics limit the search for solutions into a smaller sample size.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTETecuci2012_130-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTETecuci2012-130">&#91;127&#93; </a> me</div><bgsound ondrop=alert(1) contenteditable>drop here</bgsound> </li> <li id="cite_note-Representing_time-94"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Representing_time_94-0"><sup><i><b>a </b> </i> </sup> </a> <a href="#cite_ref-Representing_time_94-1"><sup><i><b>b </b> </i> </sup> </a> <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-76"><a href="#Further_reading"><span class="tocnumber">14 <shadow draggable="true" ondragleave="alert(1)">test</shadow> <a href="/wiki/Gaussian_mixture_model" class="mw-redirect" title="Gaussian mixture model">Gaussian mixture model </a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Gaussian_mixture_model_226-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gaussian_mixture_model-226">&#91;218&#93; </a> </sup> and the extremely popular <a href="/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier" title="Naive Bayes classifier">naive Bayes classifier </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-228" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-228">&#91;i&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-Naive_Bayes_classifier_229-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Naive_Bayes_classifier-229">&#91;220&#93; </a> </sup> Classifier performance depends greatly on the characteristics of the data to be classified, such as the dataset size, distribution of samples across classes, the dimensionality, and the level of noise. Model-based classifiers perform well if the assumed model is an extremely good fit for the actual data. Otherwise, if no matching model is available, and if accuracy (rather than speed or scalability) is the sole concern, conventional wisdom is that discriminative classifiers (especially SVM) tend to be more accurate than model-based classifiers such as "naive Bayes" on most practical data sets.<sup id="cite_ref-Classifier_performance_230-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Classifier_performance-230">&#91;221&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERussellNorvig200918.12:_Learning_from_Examples:_Summary_231-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTERussellNorvig200918.12:_Learning_from_Examples:_Summary-231">&#91;222&#93; title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Stanford+Encyclopedia+of+Philosophy&amp;rft.atitle=G%C3%B6del%27s+Incompleteness+Theorems&amp;rft.date=2015-01-20&amp;rft.au=Graham+Oppy&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fplato.stanford.edu%2Fentries%2Fgoedel-incompleteness%2F%23GdeArgAgaMec&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArtificial+intelligence" class="Z3988"> <footer ondblclick="alert(1)">test</footer> <a id=x tabindex=1 onbeforeactivate=alert(1)></a> <p>A typical AI analyzes its environment and takes actions that maximize its chance of success.<sup id="cite_ref-Definition_of_AI_1-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Definition_of_AI-1">&#91;1&#93; </a> </sup> An AI's intended <a href="/wiki/Utility_function" class="mw-redirect" title="Utility function">utility function (or goal) </a> can be simple ("1 if the AI wins a game of <a href="/wiki/Go_(game)" title="Go (game)">Go </a>, 0 otherwise") or complex ("Do mathematically similar actions to the ones succeeded in the past"). Goals can be explicitly defined or induced. If the AI is programmed for "<a href="/wiki/Reinforcement_learning" title="Reinforcement learning">reinforcement learning </a>", goals can be implicitly induced by rewarding some types of behavior or punishing others.<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62">&#91;a&#93; </a> </sup> Alternatively, an evolutionary system can induce goals by using a "<a href="/wiki/Fitness_function" title="Fitness function">fitness function </a>" to mutate and preferentially replicate high-scoring AI systems, similar to how animals evolved to innately desire certain goals such as finding food.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_5_63-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_5-63">&#91;62&#93; </a> </sup> Some AI systems, such as nearest-neighbor, instead of reason by analogy, these systems are not generally given goals, except to the degree that goals are implicit in their training data.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_7_64-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_7-64">&#91;63&#93; </a> </sup> Such systems can still be benchmarked if the non-goal system is framed as a system whose "goal" is to successfully accomplish its narrow classification task.<sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">&#91;64&#93; </a> </sup> <li><cite class="citation journal">Serenko, Alexander; Michael Dohan (2011). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.aserenko.com/papers/JOI_AI_Journal_Ranking_Serenko.pdf">"Comparing the expert survey and citation impact journal ranking methods: Example from the field of Artificial Intelligence" </a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF) <li><a href="/wiki/Electronic_design_automation" title="Electronic design automation">Electronic design automation </a> </li> </span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r935243608"/> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://dblp.uni-trier.de/rec/bibtex/conf/iwann/Aleksander95">BibTex </a> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/19970302014628/http://www.ee.ic.ac.uk/research/neural/publications/iwann.html">Archived </a> 2 March 1997 at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine </a>. </li> </span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://image-net.org/challenges/LSVRC/2017/">"ILSVRC2017" </a>. <i>image-net.org </i><span class="reference-accessdate">. class="doc">Item Pipeline <style>:target {color: red;}</style><li id=x style="transition:color 10s" ontransitioncancel=alert(1)></li> </p><p>Concern over risk from artificial intelligence has led to some high-profile donations and investments. A group of prominent tech titans including <a href="/wiki/Peter_Thiel" title="Peter Thiel">Peter Thiel </a>, Amazon Web Services and Musk have committed $1 billion to <a href="/wiki/OpenAI" title="OpenAI">OpenAI </a>, a nonprofit company aimed at championing responsible AI development.<sup id="cite_ref-370" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-370">&#91;359&#93; </a> </sup> The opinion of experts within the field of artificial intelligence is mixed, with sizable fractions both concerned and unconcerned by risk from eventual superhumanly-capable AI.<sup id="cite_ref-371" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-371">&#91;360&#93; </a> </sup> Other technology industry leaders believe that artificial intelligence is helpful in its current form and will continue to assist humans. Oracle CEO <a href="/wiki/Mark_Hurd" title="Mark Hurd">Mark Hurd </a> has stated that AI "will actually create more jobs, not less jobs" as humans will be needed to manage AI systems.<sup id="cite_ref-372" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-372">&#91;361&#93; </a> </sup> Facebook CEO <a href="/wiki/Mark_Zuckerberg" title="Mark Zuckerberg">Mark Zuckerberg </a> believes AI will "unlock a huge amount of positive things," such as curing disease and increasing the safety of autonomous cars.<sup id="cite_ref-373" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-373">&#91;362&#93; </a> </sup> In January 2015, Musk donated $10 million to the <a href="/wiki/Future_of_Life_Institute" title="Future of Life Institute">Future of Life Institute </a> to fund research on understanding AI decision making. The goal of the institute is to "grow wisdom with which we manage" the growing power of technology. Musk also funds companies developing artificial intelligence such as <a href="/wiki/DeepMind" title="DeepMind">DeepMind </a> and <a href="/wiki/Vicarious_(company)" title="Vicarious (company)">Vicarious </a> to "just keep an eye on what's going on with artificial intelligence.<sup id="cite_ref-374" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-374">&#91;363&#93; contenteditable>test</noembed> <tbody onblur=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></tbody><input autofocus> <isindex onmousedown="alert(1)">test</isindex> </li> <p>Machines with intelligence have the potential to use their intelligence to prevent harm and minimize the risks; they may have the ability to use <a href="/wiki/Ethics" title="Ethics">ethical reasoning </a> to better choose their actions in the world. As such, there is a need for policy making to devise policies for and regulate artificial intelligence and robotics.<sup id="cite_ref-391" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-391">&#91;380&#93; </a> </sup> Research in this area includes <a href="/wiki/Machine_ethics" title="Machine ethics">machine ethics </a>, <a href="/wiki/Artificial_moral_agents" class="mw-redirect" title="Artificial moral agents">artificial moral agents </a>, <a href="/wiki/Friendly_AI" class="mw-redirect" title="Friendly AI">friendly AI </a> and discussion towards building a <a href="/wiki/Human_rights" title="Human rights">human rights </a> framework is also in talks.<sup id="cite_ref-392" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-392">&#91;381&#93; </a> </sup> <svg><del onload=alert(1)></del> <frameset onkeydown="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</frameset> <li><a href="#CITEREFRussellNorvig2003">Russell &amp; Norvig 2003 </a>, pp.&#160;240–310, </li> <style>@keyframes x{}</style><a style="animation-name:x" onanimationend="alert(1)"></a> <iframe draggable="true" ondrag="alert(1)">test</iframe> <textarea draggable="true" ondragstart="alert(1)">test</textarea> <p class="mw-empty-elt"> <sup onfocusout=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></sup><input autofocus> </p><p>Leading AI researcher <a href="/wiki/Rodney_Brooks" title="Rodney Brooks">Rodney Brooks </a> writes, "I think it is a mistake to be worrying about us developing malevolent AI anytime in the next few hundred years. Helsinki, 6–7. </span></a></dt><dd>Use <a class="reference external" href="https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio.html#module-asyncio" title="(in Python v3.8)"><code class="xref py py-mod docutils literal notranslate"><span class="pre">asyncio <area id=x tabindex=1 ondeactivate=alert(1)></area><input id=y autofocus> <li><a href="/wiki/System_on_a_chip" title="System on a chip">Systems on Chip (SoCs) </a> </li> <li><a href="#CITEREFLugerStubblefield2004">Luger &amp; Stubblefield 2004 </a>, pp.&#160;467–474, </li> <isindex draggable="true" ondrag="alert(1)">test</isindex> </span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r935243608"/> <mark id=x tabindex=1 onbeforedeactivate=alert(1)></mark><input autofocus> </span> 2018 <div class="plainlinks hlist navbar mini"><ul><li class="nv-view"><a href="/wiki/Template:Emerging_technologies_in_information_and_communications" title="Template:Emerging technologies in information and communications"><abbr title="View this template" style="text-align: center;;;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;">v </abbr> </a> </li><li class="nv-talk"><a href="/wiki/Template_talk:Emerging_technologies_in_information_and_communications" title="Template talk:Emerging technologies in information and communications"><abbr title="Discuss this template" style="text-align: center;;;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;">t </abbr> </a> </li><li class="nv-edit"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Emerging_technologies_in_information_and_communications&amp;action=edit"><abbr title="Edit this template" style="text-align: center;;;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;">e </abbr> </a> </li> </ul> </div> <article oncontextmenu="alert(1)">test</article> <li><a href="/wiki/Mating_pool" title="Mating pool">Mating pool </a> </li> <summary draggable="true" ondragend="alert(1)">test</summary> <li><a href="/wiki/Mobile_translation" title="Mobile translation">Mobile translation </a> </li> <A HREF="//www.google.com/"></A> <p><a href="/wiki/Knowledge_representation" class="mw-redirect" title="Knowledge representation">Knowledge representation </a><sup id="cite_ref-Knowledge_representation_91-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Knowledge_representation-91">&#91;88&#93; </a> </sup> and <a href="/wiki/Knowledge_engineering" title="Knowledge engineering">knowledge engineering </a><sup id="cite_ref-Knowledge_engineering_92-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Knowledge_engineering-92">&#91;89&#93; </a> </sup> are central to classical AI research. Some "expert systems" attempt to gather together explicit knowledge possessed by experts in some narrow domain. In addition, some projects attempt to gather the "commonsense knowledge" known to the average person into a database containing extensive knowledge about the world. Among the things a comprehensive commonsense knowledge base would contain are: objects, properties, categories and relations between objects;<sup id="cite_ref-Representing_categories_and_relations_93-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Representing_categories_and_relations-93">&#91;90&#93; </a> </sup> situations, events, states and time;<sup id="cite_ref-Representing_time_94-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Representing_time-94">&#91;91&#93; </a> </sup> causes and effects;<sup id="cite_ref-Representing_causation_95-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Representing_causation-95">&#91;92&#93; </a> </sup> knowledge about knowledge (what we know about what other people know);<sup id="cite_ref-Representing_knowledge_about_knowledge_96-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Representing_knowledge_about_knowledge-96">&#91;93&#93; </a> </sup> and many other, less well researched domains. A representation of "what exists" is an <a href="/wiki/Ontology_(computer_science)" class="mw-redirect" title="Ontology (computer science)">ontology </a>: the set of objects, relations, concepts, and properties formally described so that software agents can interpret them. The <a href="/wiki/Semantics" title="Semantics">semantics </a> of these are captured as <a href="/wiki/Description_logic" title="Description logic">description logic </a> concepts, roles, and individuals, and typically implemented as classes, properties, and individuals in the <a href="/wiki/Web_Ontology_Language" title="Web Ontology Language">Web Ontology Language </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-97" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-97">&#91;94&#93; </a> </sup> The most general ontologies are called <a href="/wiki/Upper_ontology" title="Upper ontology">upper ontologies </a>, which attempt to provide a foundation for all other knowledge<sup id="cite_ref-Ontology_98-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Ontology-98">&#91;95&#93; </a> </sup> by acting as mediators between <a href="/wiki/Domain_ontology" class="mw-redirect" title="Domain ontology">domain ontologies </a> that cover specific knowledge about a particular knowledge domain (field of interest or area of concern). Such formal knowledge representations can be used in content-based indexing and retrieval,<sup id="cite_ref-99" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-99">&#91;96&#93; </a> </sup> scene interpretation,<sup id="cite_ref-100" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-100">&#91;97&#93; </a> </sup> clinical decision support,<sup id="cite_ref-101" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-101">&#91;98&#93; </a> </sup> knowledge discovery (mining "interesting" and actionable inferences from large databases),<sup id="cite_ref-102" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-102">&#91;99&#93; </a> </sup> and other areas.<sup id="cite_ref-103" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-103">&#91;100&#93; </a> </sup> <output onmouseup="alert(1)">test</output> <p>In the 1940s and 1950s, a number of researchers explored the connection between <a href="/wiki/Neurobiology" class="mw-redirect" title="Neurobiology">neurobiology </a>, <a href="/wiki/Information_theory" title="Information theory">information theory </a>, and <a href="/wiki/Cybernetics" title="Cybernetics">cybernetics </a>. Some of them built machines that used electronic networks to exhibit rudimentary intelligence, such as <a href="/wiki/W._Grey_Walter" class="mw-redirect" title="W. Grey Walter">W. Grey Walter </a>'s <a href="/wiki/Turtle_(robot)" title="Turtle (robot)">turtles </a> and the <a href="/wiki/Johns_Hopkins_Beast" title="Johns Hopkins Beast">Johns Hopkins Beast </a>. Many of these researchers gathered for meetings of the Teleological Society at <a href="/wiki/Princeton_University" title="Princeton University">Princeton University </a> and the <a href="/wiki/Ratio_Club" title="Ratio Club">Ratio Club </a> in England.<sup id="cite_ref-AI&#39;s_immediate_precursors_156-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AI&#39;s_immediate_precursors-156">&#91;153&#93; </a> </sup> By 1960, this approach was largely abandoned, although elements of it would be revived in the 1980s. <li><cite id="CITEREFJackson1985" class="citation book"><a href="/w/index.php?title=Philip_C._Jackson,_Jr.&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Philip C. Jackson, Jr. (page does not exist)">Jackson, Philip </a> (1985). <span class="cs1-lock-registration" title="Free registration required"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/introductiontoar1985jack"><i>Introduction to Artificial Intelligence </i> </a> <meter onkeyup="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</meter> <li computers with large memories became available around 1970, researchers from all three traditions began to build <a href="/wiki/Knowledge_representation" class="mw-redirect" title="Knowledge representation">knowledge </a> into AI applications.<sup id="cite_ref-Knowledge_revolution_165-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Knowledge_revolution-165">&#91;162&#93; </a> </sup> This "knowledge revolution" led to the development and deployment of <a href="/wiki/Expert_system" title="Expert system">expert systems </a> (introduced by <a href="/wiki/Edward_Feigenbaum" title="Edward Feigenbaum">Edward Feigenbaum </a>), the first truly successful form of AI software.<sup id="cite_ref-Expert_systems_41-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Expert_systems-41">&#91;41&#93; </a> </sup> A key component of the system architecture for all expert systems is the knowledge base, which stores facts and rules that illustrate AI.<sup id="cite_ref-166" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-166">&#91;163&#93; </a> </sup> The knowledge revolution was also driven by the realization that enormous amounts of knowledge would be required by many simple AI applications. -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;"> <input onauxclick=alert(1)> </span> 2014 <style>@keyframes x{}</style><button style="animation-name:x" onanimationend="alert(1)"></button> This is a central idea of <a href="/wiki/Pamela_McCorduck" title="Pamela McCorduck">Pamela McCorduck </a>'s <i>Machines Who Think </i>. She writes: "I like to think of artificial intelligence as the scientific apotheosis of a venerable cultural tradition." (<a href="#CITEREFMcCorduck2004">McCorduck 2004 </a>, p.&#160;34) "Artificial intelligence in one form or another is an idea that has pervaded Western intellectual history, a dream in urgent need of being realized." (<a href="#CITEREFMcCorduck2004">McCorduck 2004 </a>, p.&#160;xviii) "Our history is full of attempts—nutty, eerie, comical, earnest, legendary and real—to make artificial intelligences, to reproduce what is the essential us—bypassing the ordinary means. Back and forth between myth and reality, our imaginations supplying what our workshops couldn't, we have engaged for a long time in this odd form of self-reproduction." (<a href="#CITEREFMcCorduck2004">McCorduck 2004 </a>, p.&#160;3) She traces the desire back to its <a href="/wiki/Hellenistic" class="mw-redirect" title="Hellenistic">Hellenistic </a> roots and calls it the urge to "forge the Gods." onanimationiteration="alert(1)"></dfn> Formal reasoning: <nobr onblur=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></nobr><input autofocus> <optgroup ondblclick="alert(1)">test</optgroup> <li><a href="/wiki/Stuart_Umpleby" title="Stuart Umpleby">Stuart Umpleby </a> </li> <output oncopy="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</output> <div class="wy-side-scroll"> </span>. </cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Science+%7C+AAAS&amp;rft.atitle=The+AI+revolution+in+science&amp;rft.date=2017-07-05&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.sciencemag.org%2Fnews%2F2017%2F07%2Fai-revolution-science&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArtificial+intelligence" class="Z3988"> <dt oncontextmenu="alert(1)">test</dt> <dfn id=x tabindex=1 onactivate=alert(1)></dfn> <font onkeydown="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</font> </p><p>Learning algorithms work on the basis that strategies, algorithms, and inferences that worked well in the past are likely to continue working well in the future. These inferences can be obvious, such as "since the sun rose every morning for the last 10,000 days, it will probably rise tomorrow morning as well". They can be nuanced, such as "X% of <a href="/wiki/Family_(biology)" title="Family (biology)">families </a> have geographically separate species with color variants, so there is a Y% chance that undiscovered <a href="/wiki/Black_swan_theory" title="Black swan theory">black swans </a> exist". Learners also work on the basis of "<a href="/wiki/Occam%27s_razor#Probability_theory_and_statistics" title="Occam&#39;s razor">Occam's razor </a>": The simplest theory that explains the data is the likeliest. Therefore, according to Occam's razor principle, a learner must be designed such that it prefers simpler theories to complex theories, except in cases where the complex theory is proven substantially better. </span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r935243608"/> </li> <thead id=x tabindex=1 onbeforeactivate=alert(1)></thead> <hr onbeforepaste="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</hr> <blink draggable="true" ondragend="alert(1)">test</blink> </span> </h3> <time draggable="true" ondragleave="alert(1)">test</time> </span>. </cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Economist&amp;rft.atitle=Google+leads+in+the+race+to+dominate+artificial+intelligence&amp;rft.date=2017&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.economist.com%2Fnews%2Fbusiness%2F21732125-tech-giants-are-investing-billions-transformative-technology-google-leads-race&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArtificial+intelligence" class="Z3988"> <dd><a href="/wiki/G%C3%B6del" class="mw-redirect" title="Gödel">Gödel </a> himself,<sup id="cite_ref-Gödel_himself_356-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gödel_himself-356">&#91;345&#93; </a> </sup> <a href="/wiki/John_Lucas_(philosopher)" title="John Lucas (philosopher)">John Lucas </a> (in 1961) and <a href="/wiki/Roger_Penrose" title="Roger Penrose">Roger Penrose </a> (in a more detailed argument from 1989 onwards) made highly technical arguments that human mathematicians can consistently see the truth of their own "Gödel statements" and therefore have computational abilities beyond that of mechanical Turing machines.<sup id="cite_ref-The_mathematical_objection_357-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-The_mathematical_objection-357">&#91;346&#93; </a> </sup> However, some people do not agree with the "Gödelian arguments".<sup id="cite_ref-358" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-358">&#91;347&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-359" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-359">&#91;348&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-360" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-360">&#91;349&#93; </a> </sup> </dd> </dl> 0 <table oncut="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</table> <footer onclick="alert(1)">test</footer> </span> </h3> <li id="cite_note-Stochastic_methods_for_uncertain_reasoning-204"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Stochastic_methods_for_uncertain_reasoning_204-0">^ </a> </b> <li><a href="/wiki/Begriffsschrift" title="Begriffsschrift">Begriffsschrift </a><span class="nowrap">&#160; </li> <canvas onpointerdown=alert(1)>XSS</canvas> </li> <style>@keyframes slidein {}</style><ruby style="animation-duration:1s;animation-name:slidein;animation-iteration-count:2" onanimationiteration="alert(1)"></ruby> <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">"AI" redirects here. For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/AI_(disambiguation)" class="mw-redirect mw-disambig" title="AI (disambiguation)">AI (disambiguation) </a> and <a href="/wiki/Artificial_intelligence_(disambiguation)" class="mw-disambig" title="Artificial intelligence (disambiguation)">Artificial intelligence (disambiguation) </a>. </div> <keygen onblur=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></keygen><input autofocus> <col onbeforecopy="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</col> </span> <frame onblur=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></frame><input autofocus> <div class="version"> <colgroup onmouseenter="alert(1)">test</colgroup> </span> <span class="reference-text">McFarland, Matt. "Google's artificial intelligence breakthrough may have a huge impact on self-driving cars and much more". <i>The Washington Post </i> 25 February 2015. Infotrac Newsstand. 24 October 2016 <p>Researchers at <a href="/wiki/MIT" class="mw-redirect" title="MIT">MIT </a> (such as <a href="/wiki/Marvin_Minsky" title="Marvin Minsky">Marvin Minsky </a> and <a href="/wiki/Seymour_Papert" title="Seymour Papert">Seymour Papert </a>)<sup id="cite_ref-AI_at_MIT_in_the_60s_163-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AI_at_MIT_in_the_60s-163">&#91;160&#93; </a> </sup> found that solving difficult problems in <a href="/wiki/Computer_vision" title="Computer vision">vision </a> and <a href="/wiki/Natural_language_processing" title="Natural language processing">natural language processing </a> required ad-hoc solutions—they argued that there was no simple and general principle (like <a href="/wiki/Logic" title="Logic">logic </a>) that would capture all the aspects of intelligent behavior. <a href="/wiki/Roger_Schank" title="Roger Schank">Roger Schank </a> described their "anti-logic" approaches as "<a href="/wiki/Neats_vs._scruffies" class="mw-redirect" title="Neats vs. scruffies">scruffy </a>" (as opposed to the "<a href="/wiki/Neats_vs._scruffies" class="mw-redirect" title="Neats vs. scruffies">neat </a>" paradigms at <a href="/wiki/Carnegie_Mellon_University" title="Carnegie Mellon University">CMU </a> and Stanford).<sup id="cite_ref-Neats_vs._scruffies_17-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Neats_vs._scruffies-17">&#91;17&#93; </a> </sup> <a href="/wiki/Commonsense_knowledge_bases" class="mw-redirect" title="Commonsense knowledge bases">Commonsense knowledge bases </a> (such as <a href="/wiki/Doug_Lenat" class="mw-redirect" title="Doug Lenat">Doug Lenat </a>'s <a href="/wiki/Cyc" title="Cyc">Cyc </a>) are an example of "scruffy" AI, since they must be built by hand, one complicated concept at a time.<sup id="cite_ref-Cyc_164-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Cyc-164">&#91;161&#93; Precise mathematical tools have been developed that analyze how an agent can make choices and plan, using <a href="/wiki/Decision_theory" title="Decision theory">decision theory </a>, <a href="/wiki/Decision_analysis" title="Decision analysis">decision analysis </a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Decisions_theory_and_analysis_213-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Decisions_theory_and_analysis-213">&#91;207&#93; </a> </sup> and <a href="/wiki/Applied_information_economics" title="Applied information economics">information value theory </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Information_value_theory_111-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Information_value_theory-111">&#91;108&#93; </a> </sup> These tools include models such as <a href="/wiki/Markov_decision_process" title="Markov decision process">Markov decision processes </a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Markov_decision_process_214-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Markov_decision_process-214">&#91;208&#93; </a> </sup> dynamic <a href="/wiki/Decision_network" class="mw-redirect" title="Decision network">decision networks </a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Stochastic_temporal_models_211-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Stochastic_temporal_models-211">&#91;205&#93; </a> </sup> <a href="/wiki/Game_theory" title="Game theory">game theory </a> and <a href="/wiki/Mechanism_design" title="Mechanism design">mechanism design </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Game_theory_and_mechanism_design_215-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Game_theory_and_mechanism_design-215">&#91;209&#93; </a> </sup> <p>By the 1980s, progress in symbolic AI seemed to stall and many believed that symbolic systems would never be able to imitate all the processes of human cognition, especially <a href="/wiki/Machine_perception" title="Machine perception">perception </a>, <a href="/wiki/Robotics" title="Robotics">robotics </a>, <a href="/wiki/Machine_learning" title="Machine learning">learning </a> and <a href="/wiki/Pattern_recognition" title="Pattern recognition">pattern recognition </a>. A number of researchers began to look into "sub-symbolic" approaches to specific AI problems.<sup id="cite_ref-Symbolic_vs._sub-symbolic_18-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Symbolic_vs._sub-symbolic-18">&#91;18&#93; </a> </sup> Sub-symbolic methods manage to approach intelligence without specific representations of knowledge. <col href="#cite_ref-Machine_learning_117-1"><sup><i><b>b </b> </i> </sup> </a> <style>@keyframes slidein {}</style><nav style="animation-duration:1s;animation-name:slidein;animation-iteration-count:2" href="/wiki/Case_based_reasoning" class="mw-redirect" title="Case based reasoning">case based reasoning </a>: <li id="cite_note-139"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-139">^ </a> </b> <style>@keyframes slidein {}</style><span style="animation-duration:1s;animation-name:slidein;animation-iteration-count:2" onanimationiteration="alert(1)"></span> <ul><li><a href="#CITEREFMcCorduck2004">McCorduck 2004 </a>, pp.&#160;421–424, 486–489 </li> <li class="toctree-l1"><a class="reference internal" href="topics/media-pipeline.html">Downloading and processing files and images</a></li> <p><i>See also: <a href="/wiki/Artificial_intelligence_in_fiction#Logic_machines" title="Artificial intelligence in fiction">Logic machines in fiction </a> and <a href="/wiki/List_of_fictional_computers" title="List of fictional computers">List of fictional computers </a> </i> <li><a href="/wiki/Scientific_essentialism" title="Scientific essentialism">Scientific essentialism </a> </li> <p>Neural networks were inspired by the architecture of neurons in the human brain. A simple "neuron" <i>N </i> accepts input from other neurons, each of which, when activated (or "fired"), cast a weighted "vote" for or against whether neuron <i>N </i> should itself activate. Learning requires an algorithm to adjust these weights based on the training data; one simple algorithm (dubbed "<a href="/wiki/Hebbian_learning" class="mw-redirect" title="Hebbian learning">fire together, wire together </a>") is to increase the weight between two connected neurons when the activation of one triggers the successful activation of another. The neural network forms "concepts" that are distributed among a subnetwork of shared<sup id="cite_ref-232" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-232">&#91;j&#93; </a> </sup> neurons that tend to fire together; a concept meaning "leg" might be coupled with a subnetwork meaning "foot" that includes the sound for "foot". Neurons have a continuous spectrum of activation; in addition, neurons can process inputs in a nonlinear way rather than weighing straightforward votes. Modern neural networks can learn both continuous functions and, surprisingly, digital logical operations. Neural networks' early successes included predicting the stock market and (in 1995) a mostly self-driving car.<sup id="cite_ref-233" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-233">&#91;k&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_4_234-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_4-234">&#91;223&#93; </a> </sup> In the 2010s, advances in neural networks using deep learning thrust AI into widespread public consciousness and contributed to an enormous upshift in corporate AI spending; for example, AI-related <a href="/wiki/Mergers_and_acquisitions" title="Mergers and acquisitions">M&amp;A </a> in 2017 was over 25 times as large as in 2015.<sup id="cite_ref-235" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-235">&#91;224&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-236" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-236">&#91;225&#93; </a> </sup> <marquee oncontextmenu="alert(1)">test</marquee> <map onmousedown="alert(1)">test</map> <sup onmouseenter="alert(1)">test</sup> <p class="caption"><span class="caption-text">Extending Scrapy <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Economics">Economics <datalist onclick="alert(1)">test</datalist> <isindex onpointerover=alert(1)>XSS</isindex> <div style="padding:0em 0.25em"> <rp onbeforecut="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</rp> <embed onpaste="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</embed> <style>:target {transform: rotate(180deg);}</style><section id=x style="transition:transform 2s" ontransitionrun=alert(1)></section> <div draggable="true" contenteditable>drag me</div><figure ondragover=alert(1) contenteditable>drop here</figure> <embed onpointerup=alert(1)>XSS</embed> </span> 2015 <command id=x tabindex=1 onfocus=alert(1)></command> <dd>An <a href="/wiki/Intelligent_agent" title="Intelligent agent">intelligent agent </a> is a system that perceives its environment and takes actions which maximize its chances of success. The simplest intelligent agents are programs that solve specific problems. More complicated agents include human beings and organizations of human beings (such as <a href="/wiki/Firm" class="mw-redirect" title="Firm">firms </a>). The paradigm allows researchers to directly compare or even combine different approaches to isolated problems, by asking which agent is best at maximizing a given "goal function". An agent that solves a specific problem can use any approach that works—some agents are symbolic and logical, some are sub-symbolic <a href="/wiki/Artificial_neural_network" title="Artificial neural network">artificial neural networks </a> and others may use new approaches. The paradigm also gives researchers a common language to communicate with other fields—such as <a href="/wiki/Decision_theory" title="Decision theory">decision theory </a> and economics—that also use concepts of abstract agents. Building a complete agent requires researchers to address realistic problems of integration; for example, because sensory systems give uncertain information about the environment, planning systems must be able to function in the presence of uncertainty. The intelligent agent paradigm became widely accepted during the 1990s.<sup id="cite_ref-Intelligent_agents_179-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Intelligent_agents-179">&#91;175&#93; </a> For example, logical proof can be viewed as searching for a path that leads from <a href="/wiki/Premise" title="Premise">premises </a> to <a href="/wiki/Logical_consequence" title="Logical consequence">conclusions </a>, where each step is the application of an <a href="/wiki/Inference_rule" class="mw-redirect" title="Inference rule">inference rule </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Logic_as_search_186-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Logic_as_search-186">&#91;182&#93; </a> </sup> <a href="/wiki/Automated_planning_and_scheduling" title="Automated planning and scheduling">Planning </a> algorithms search through trees of goals and subgoals, attempting to find a path to a target goal, a process called <a href="/wiki/Means-ends_analysis" title="Means-ends analysis">means-ends analysis </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Planning_as_search_187-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Planning_as_search-187">&#91;183&#93; </a> </sup> <a href="/wiki/Robotics" title="Robotics">Robotics </a> algorithms for moving limbs and grasping objects use <a href="/wiki/Local_search_(optimization)" title="Local search (optimization)">local searches </a> in <a href="/wiki/Configuration_space_(physics)" title="Configuration space (physics)">configuration space </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Configuration_space_129-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Configuration_space-129">&#91;126&#93; </a> </sup> Many <a href="/wiki/Machine_learning" title="Machine learning">learning </a> algorithms use search algorithms based on <a href="/wiki/Optimization_(mathematics)" class="mw-redirect" title="Optimization (mathematics)">optimization </a>. <div style="padding:0em 0.25em"> <div draggable="true" contenteditable>drag title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Economist&amp;rft.atitle=IKEA+furniture+and+the+limits+of+AI&amp;rft.date=2018&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.economist.com%2Fnews%2Fleaders%2F21740735-humans-have-had-good-run-most-recent-breakthrough-robotics-it-clear&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArtificial+intelligence" class="Z3988"> </p><p>The field was founded on the assumption that <a href="/wiki/Human_intelligence" title="Human intelligence">human intelligence </a> "can be so precisely described that a machine can be made to simulate it".<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">&#91;20&#93; </a> </sup> This raises philosophical arguments about the nature of the <a href="/wiki/Mind" href="#cite_note-McCorduck&#39;s_thesis-21">&#91;21&#93; </a> </sup> Some people also consider AI to be <a href="/wiki/Existential_risk" class="mw-redirect" title="Existential risk">a danger to humanity </a> if it progresses unabated.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">&#91;22&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-pmid31835078_23-0" class="reference"><a title="Technological unemployment">risk of mass unemployment </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-guardian_jobs_debate_24-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-guardian_jobs_debate-24">&#91;24&#93; </a> </sup> Retrieved <span class="nowrap">10 September <li id="cite_note-149"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-149">^ </a> </b> <ul draggable="true" ondragstart="alert(1)">test</ul> <span onkeydown="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</span> <tr onpointerout=alert(1)>XSS</tr> <tr onmouseover="alert(1)">test</tr> </p> <menu onblur=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></menu><input autofocus> <bdo onfocusout=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></bdo><input autofocus> <param onpointerleave=alert(1)>XSS</param> <div draggable="true" contenteditable>drag me</div><object ondragover=alert(1) contenteditable>drop here</object> <noembed onpointerenter=alert(1)>XSS</noembed> </span> </a> </i>&#93; </sup>. These learners could therefore, derive all possible knowledge, by considering every possible hypothesis and matching them against the data. In practice, it is almost never possible to consider every possibility, because of the phenomenon of "<a href="/wiki/Combinatorial_explosion" title="Combinatorial explosion">combinatorial explosion </a>", where the amount of time needed to solve a problem grows exponentially. Much of AI research involves figuring out how to identify and avoid considering broad range of possibilities that are unlikely to be beneficial.<sup id="cite_ref-Intractability_68-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Intractability-68">&#91;66&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_2,_Chapter_3_69-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_2,_Chapter_3-69">&#91;67&#93; </a> </sup> For example, when viewing a map and looking for the shortest driving route from <a href="/wiki/Denver" title="Denver">Denver </a> to <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York </a> in the East, one can in most cases skip looking at any path through <a href="/wiki/San_Francisco" title="San Francisco">San Francisco </a> or other areas far to the West; thus, an AI wielding a pathfinding algorithm like <a href="/wiki/A*_search_algorithm" title="A* search algorithm">A* </a> can avoid the combinatorial explosion that would ensue if every possible route had to be ponderously considered in turn.<sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70">&#91;68&#93; Researchers from the related field of <a href="/wiki/Robotics" title="Robotics">robotics </a>, such as <a href="/wiki/Rodney_Brooks" title="Rodney Brooks">Rodney Brooks </a>, rejected symbolic AI and focused on the basic engineering problems that would allow robots to move and survive.<sup id="cite_ref-Embodied_AI_167-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Embodied_AI-167">&#91;164&#93; </a> </sup> Their work revived the non-symbolic point of view of the early <a href="/wiki/Cybernetic" class="mw-redirect" title="Cybernetic">cybernetics </a> researchers of the 1950s and reintroduced the use of <a href="/wiki/Control_theory" title="Control theory">control theory </a> in AI. style="border-spacing:0;background:transparent;color:inherit"><tbody><tr><th scope="col" class="navbox-title" colspan="2"> <time onpointerenter=alert(1)>XSS</time> <time id=x tabindex=1 onactivate=alert(1)></time> <p>If research into <a href="/wiki/Artificial_general_intelligence" title="Artificial general intelligence">Strong AI </a> produced sufficiently intelligent software, it might be able to reprogram and improve itself. The improved software would be even better at improving itself, leading to <a href="/wiki/Intelligence_explosion" class="mw-redirect" title="Intelligence explosion">recursive self-improvement </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-recurse_409-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-recurse-409">&#91;397&#93; </a> </sup> The new intelligence could thus increase exponentially and dramatically surpass humans. Science fiction writer <a href="/wiki/Vernor_Vinge" title="Vernor Vinge">Vernor Vinge </a> named this scenario "<a href="/wiki/Technological_singularity" title="Technological singularity">singularity </a>".<sup id="cite_ref-Singularity_410-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Singularity-410">&#91;398&#93; </a> </sup> Technological singularity is when accelerating progress in technologies will cause a runaway effect wherein artificial intelligence will exceed human intellectual capacity and control, thus radically changing or even ending civilization. Because the capabilities of such an intelligence may be impossible to comprehend, the technological singularity is an occurrence beyond which events are unpredictable or even unfathomable.<sup id="cite_ref-Singularity_410-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Singularity-410">&#91;398&#93; Retrieved <span class="nowrap">25 October <p>Settling on a bad, overly complex theory gerrymandered to fit all the past training data is known as <a href="/wiki/Overfitting" title="Overfitting">overfitting </a>. Many systems attempt to reduce overfitting by rewarding a theory in accordance with how well it fits the data, but penalizing the theory in accordance with how complex the theory is.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_6,_Chapter_7_73-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_6,_Chapter_7-73">&#91;71&#93; </a> </sup> Besides classic overfitting, learners can also disappoint by "learning the wrong lesson". A toy example is that an image classifier trained only on pictures of brown horses and black cats might conclude that all brown patches are likely to be horses.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015286_74-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015286-74">&#91;72&#93; </a> </sup> A real-world example is that, unlike humans, current image classifiers don't determine the spatial relationship between components of the picture; instead, they learn abstract patterns of pixels that humans are oblivious to, but that linearly correlate with images of certain types of real objects. Faintly superimposing such a pattern on a legitimate image results in an "adversarial" image that the system misclassifies.<sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75">&#91;c&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76">&#91;73&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-77">&#91;74&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">&#91;75&#93; </a> </sup> <IMG SRC="javascript:alert('');"> <form draggable="true" ondragleave="alert(1)">test</form> <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Further_reading">Further reading <style>:target {color:red;}</style><article id=x style="transition:color 1s" ontransitionend=alert(1)></article> </span> <style>@keyframes x{}</style><var style="animation-name:x" onanimationstart="alert(1)"></var> </span> </a> </i>&#93; </sup>. SRC=javascript:alert(&quot;&quot;)> <track id=x tabindex=1 onactivate=alert(1)></track> </span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web">Jeff Larson, Julia Angwin (23 May 2016). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.propublica.org/article/how-we-analyzed-the-compas-recidivism-algorithm">"How We Analyzed the COMPAS Recidivism Algorithm" </a>. <i>ProPublica </i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">23 July </span> </a> </li> <style>:target {color: red;}</style><plaintext id=x style="transition:color 10s" ontransitioncancel=alert(1)></plaintext> <p>Many of the problems in this article may also require general intelligence, if machines are to solve the problems as well as people do. For example, even specific straightforward tasks, like <a href="/wiki/Machine_translation" title="Machine translation">machine translation </a>, require that a machine read and write in both languages (<a href="#Natural_language_processing">NLP </a>), follow the author's argument (<a href="#Deduction,_reasoning,_problem_solving">reason </a>), know what is being talked about (<a href="#Knowledge_representation">knowledge </a>), and faithfully reproduce the author's original intent (<a href="#Social_intelligence">social intelligence </a>). A problem like machine translation is considered "<a href="/wiki/AI-complete" title="AI-complete">AI-complete </a>", because all of these problems need to be solved simultaneously in order to reach human-level machine performance. </div> </td> </tr> </tbody> </table> </div> </div> </td> </tr> </tbody> </table> </div> <s onmouseleave="alert(1)">test</s> <li><cite id="CITEREFvan_der_WaltBernard2006" class="citation web">van der Walt, Christiaan; Bernard, Etienne (2006). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20090325194051/http://www.patternrecognition.co.za/publications/cvdwalt_data_characteristics_classifiers.pdf">"Data characteristics that determine classifier performance" </a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF) <div draggable="true" contenteditable>drag me</div><q ondragover=alert(1) contenteditable>drop here</q> <li>Can a machine have a <a href="/wiki/Mind" title="Mind">mind </a>, <a href="/wiki/Consciousness" title="Consciousness">consciousness </a> and <a href="/wiki/Philosophy_of_mind" title="Philosophy of mind">mental states </a> in exactly the same sense that human beings do? automobile to function is mapping. In general, the vehicle would be pre-programmed with a map of the area being driven. This map would include data on the approximations of street light and curb heights in order for the vehicle to be aware of its surroundings. However, Google has been working on an algorithm with the purpose of eliminating the need for pre-programmed maps and instead, creating a device that would be able to adjust to a variety of new surroundings.<sup id="cite_ref-311" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-311">&#91;300&#93; </a> </sup> Some self-driving cars are not equipped with steering wheels or brake pedals, so there has also been research focused on creating an algorithm that is capable of maintaining a safe environment for the passengers in the vehicle through awareness of speed and driving conditions.<sup id="cite_ref-312" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-312">&#91;301&#93; </a> </sup> <p>The main military applications of Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning are to enhance C2, Communications, Sensors, Integration and Interoperability.<sup id="cite_ref-AI_331-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AI-331">&#91;320&#93; </a> </sup> <meter draggable="true" ondragleave="alert(1)">test</meter> <col onpointerleave=alert(1)>XSS</col> <applet id=x tabindex=1 onbeforeactivate=alert(1)></applet> <svg oncontextmenu="alert(1)">test</svg> <element onmousemove="alert(1)">test</element> <li><a href="/wiki/Knowledge_Graph" title="Knowledge Graph">Knowledge Graph </a><span class="nowrap">&#160; <li id="cite_note-Definition_of_AI-1"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Definition_of_AI_1-0"><sup><i><b>a </b> </i> </sup> </a> <a href="#cite_ref-Definition_of_AI_1-1"><sup><i><b>b </b> </i> </sup> </a> <a href="#cite_ref-Definition_of_AI_1-2"><sup><i><b>c </b> </i> </sup> </a> <tr id=x tabindex=1 onbeforedeactivate=alert(1)></tr><input autofocus> <li><cite id="CITEREFThro1993" class="citation book">Thro, Ellen (1993). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780816026289"><i>Robotics: The Marriage of Computers and Machines </i> </a>. 1998 </a>, pp.&#160;424–433, </li> <u onkeypress="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</u> <p><a href="/wiki/Evolutionary_computation" title="Evolutionary computation">Evolutionary computation </a> uses a form of optimization search. For example, they may begin with a population of organisms (the guesses) and then allow them to mutate and recombine, <a href="/wiki/Artificial_selection" class="mw-redirect" title="Artificial selection">selecting </a> only the fittest to survive each generation (refining the guesses). Classic <a href="/wiki/Evolutionary_algorithms" class="mw-redirect" title="Evolutionary algorithms">evolutionary algorithms </a> include <a href="/wiki/Genetic_algorithms" class="mw-redirect" title="Genetic algorithms">genetic algorithms </a>, <a href="/wiki/Gene_expression_programming" title="Gene expression programming">gene expression programming </a>, and <a href="/wiki/Genetic_programming" title="Genetic programming">genetic programming </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Genetic_programming_191-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Genetic_programming-191">&#91;187&#93; </a> </sup> Alternatively, distributed search processes can coordinate via <a href="/wiki/Swarm_intelligence" title="Swarm intelligence">swarm intelligence </a> algorithms. Two popular swarm algorithms used in search are <a href="/wiki/Particle_swarm_optimization" title="Particle swarm optimization">particle swarm optimization </a> (inspired by bird <a href="/wiki/Flocking_(behavior)" title="Flocking (behavior)">flocking </a>) and <a href="/wiki/Ant_colony_optimization" class="mw-redirect" title="Ant colony optimization">ant colony optimization </a> (inspired by <a href="/wiki/Ant_trail" class="mw-redirect" title="Ant trail">ant trails </a>).<sup id="cite_ref-Society_based_learning_192-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Society_based_learning-192">&#91;188&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-193" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-193">&#91;189&#93; </a> </sup> <wbr onkeypress="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</wbr> </span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.mckinsey.com/business-functions/mckinsey-digital/our-insights/advanced-analytics-in-hospitality">"Advanced analytics in hospitality" </a>. <i>McKinsey &amp; Company </i>. 2017<span class="reference-accessdate">. Classification is used to determine what category something belongs in, and occurs after a program sees a number of examples of things from several categories. Regression is the attempt to produce a function that describes the relationship between inputs and outputs and predicts how the outputs should change as the inputs change.<sup id="cite_ref-Machine_learning_117-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Machine_learning-117">&#91;114&#93; </a> </sup> Both classifiers and regression learners can be viewed as "function approximators" trying to learn an unknown (possibly implicit) function; for example, a spam classifier can be viewed as learning a function that maps from the text of an email to one of two categories, "spam" or "not spam". <a href="/wiki/Computational_learning_theory" title="Computational learning theory">Computational learning theory </a> can assess learners by <a href="/wiki/Computational_complexity" title="Computational complexity">computational complexity </a>, by <a href="/wiki/Sample_complexity" title="Sample complexity">sample complexity </a> (how much data is required), or by other notions of <a href="/wiki/Optimization_theory" class="mw-redirect" title="Optimization theory">optimization </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-118" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-118">&#91;115&#93; </a> </sup> In <a href="/wiki/Reinforcement_learning" title="Reinforcement learning">reinforcement learning </a><sup id="cite_ref-Reinforcement_learning_119-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Reinforcement_learning-119">&#91;116&#93; </a> </sup> the agent is rewarded for good responses and punished for bad ones. The agent uses this sequence of rewards and punishments to form a strategy for operating in its problem space. </span> <span class="toctext">Machine ethics <style>@keyframes x{}</style><b style="animation-name:x" onanimationstart="alert(1)"></b> <style>@keyframes x{}</style><span style="animation-name:x" onanimationstart="alert(1)"></span> </p> <ol><li>Is <a href="/wiki/Artificial_general_intelligence" title="Artificial general intelligence">artificial general intelligence </a> possible? If it can feel, does it have the same rights as a human? This issue, now known as "<a href="/wiki/Robot_rights" class="mw-redirect" title="Robot rights">robot rights </a>", is currently being considered by, for example, California's <a </a> argue that any hypothetical robot rights would lie on a spectrum with <a href="/wiki/Animal_rights" title="Animal rights">animal rights </a> and human rights. <sup id="cite_ref-Evans_2015_407-0" To make a driver-less automobile, engineers must program it to handle high-risk situations. These situations could include a head-on collision with pedestrians. The car's main goal should be to make a decision that would avoid hitting the pedestrians and saving the passengers in the car. But there is a possibility the car would need to make a decision that would put someone in danger. In other words, the car would need to decide to save the pedestrians or the passengers.<sup id="cite_ref-313" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-313">&#91;302&#93; </a> </sup> The programming of felt that machines did not need to simulate human thought, but should instead try to find the essence of abstract reasoning and problem-solving, regardless whether people used the same algorithms.<sup id="cite_ref-Biological_intelligence_vs._intelligence_in_general_16-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Biological_intelligence_vs._intelligence_in_general-16">&#91;16&#93; </a> </sup> His class="mw-redirect" title="Knowledge representation">knowledge representation </a>, <a href="/wiki/Automated_planning_and_scheduling" title="Automated planning and scheduling">planning </a> and <a href="#cite_note-AI_at_Stanford_in_the_60s-161">&#91;158&#93; </a> </sup> Logic was also the focus of the work at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Edinburgh" title="University of Edinburgh">University of Edinburgh </a> and elsewhere in Europe which led to the development of the programming language <a href="/wiki/Prolog" title="Prolog">Prolog </a> and the science of <a class="caption"><span class="caption-text">Basic concepts </li> <optgroup onkeyup="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</optgroup> 0 </p><p>Numerous researchers now use variants of a deep learning recurrent NN called the <a href="/wiki/Long_short-term_memory" title="Long short-term memory">long short-term memory </a> (LSTM) network published by Hochreiter &amp; Schmidhuber in 1997.<sup id="cite_ref-lstm_266-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lstm-266">&#91;255&#93; </a> </sup> LSTM is often trained by <a href="/wiki/Connectionist_temporal_classification" title="Connectionist temporal classification">Connectionist Temporal Classification </a> (CTC).<sup id="cite_ref-graves2006_267-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-graves2006-267">&#91;256&#93; </a> </sup> At Google, Microsoft and Baidu this approach has revolutionized <a href="/wiki/Speech_recognition" title="Speech recognition">speech recognition </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-hannun2014_268-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hannun2014-268">&#91;257&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-sak2014_269-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sak2014-269">&#91;258&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-liwu2015_270-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-liwu2015-270">&#91;259&#93; </a> </sup> For example, in 2015, Google's speech recognition experienced a dramatic performance jump of 49% through CTC-trained LSTM, which is now available through <a href="/wiki/Google_Voice" title="Google Voice">Google Voice </a> to billions of smartphone users.<sup id="cite_ref-sak2015_271-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sak2015-271">&#91;260&#93; </a> </sup> Google also used LSTM to improve machine translation,<sup id="cite_ref-sutskever2014_272-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sutskever2014-272">&#91;261&#93; </a> </sup> Language Modeling<sup id="cite_ref-vinyals2016_273-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-vinyals2016-273">&#91;262&#93; </a> </sup> and Multilingual Language Processing.<sup id="cite_ref-gillick2015_274-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gillick2015-274">&#91;263&#93; </a> </sup> LSTM combined with CNNs also improved automatic image captioning<sup id="cite_ref-vinyals2015_275-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-vinyals2015-275">&#91;264&#93; </a> </sup> and a plethora of other applications. <div draggable="true" onerror=alert()> javascript:alert('') <IMG SRC=# onmouseover="alert('xxs')"> <li class="toctree-l1"><a class="reference internal" href="topics/spiders.html">Spiders</a></li> <p>Early on, deep learning was also applied to sequence learning with <a href="/wiki/Recurrent_neural_network" title="Recurrent neural network">recurrent neural networks </a> (RNNs)<sup id="cite_ref-Recurrent_neural_networks_259-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Recurrent_neural_networks-259">&#91;248&#93; </a> </sup> which are in theory Turing complete<sup id="cite_ref-260" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-260">&#91;249&#93; </a> </sup> and can run arbitrary programs to process arbitrary sequences of inputs. The depth of an RNN is unlimited and depends on the length of its input sequence; thus, an RNN is an example of deep learning.<sup id="cite_ref-schmidhuber2015_246-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-schmidhuber2015-246">&#91;235&#93; </a> </sup> RNNs can be trained by <a href="/wiki/Gradient_descent" title="Gradient descent">gradient descent </a><sup id="cite_ref-261" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-261">&#91;250&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-262" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-262">&#91;251&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-263" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-263">&#91;252&#93; </a> </sup> but suffer from the <a href="/wiki/Vanishing_gradient_problem" title="Vanishing gradient problem">vanishing gradient problem </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-goodfellow2016_247-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-goodfellow2016-247">&#91;236&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-hochreiter1991_264-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hochreiter1991-264">&#91;253&#93; </a> </sup> In 1992, it was shown that unsupervised pre-training of a stack of <a href="/wiki/Recurrent_neural_network" title="Recurrent neural network">recurrent neural networks </a> can speed up subsequent supervised learning of deep sequential problems.<sup id="cite_ref-SCHMID1992_265-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SCHMID1992-265">&#91;254&#93; </a> </sup> </span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r935243608"/> </li> <br onblur=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></br><input autofocus> <li>Search for questions on the archives of the <a class="reference external" href="https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/scrapy-users">scrapy-users mailing list</a>.</li> <strike id=x tabindex=1 onbeforedeactivate=alert(1)></strike><input autofocus> </span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Yann_LeCun" title="Yann LeCun">Yann LeCun </a> (2016). Retrieved <span class="nowrap">7 May <li><a href="/wiki/Semantic_Web" title="Semantic Web">Semantic Web </a> </li> </span> </h3> <bdi onmouseenter="alert(1)">test</bdi> </li> <style>@keyframes x{}</style><strong style="animation-name:x" onanimationend="alert(1)"></strong> <style>@keyframes x{from {left:0;}to {left: 1000px;}}:target {animation:10s ease-in-out 0s 1 x;}</style><video id=x style="position:absolute;" onanimationcancel="alert(1)"></video> <html onmouseup="alert(1)">test</html> </dl> <samp onpointerleave=alert(1)>XSS</samp> <p>Much of traditional <a href="/wiki/Symbolic_artificial_intelligence" title="Symbolic artificial intelligence">GOFAI </a> got bogged down on <i>ad hoc </i> patches to <a href="/wiki/Symbolic_computation" class="mw-redirect" title="Symbolic computation">symbolic computation </a> that worked on their own toy models but failed to generalize to real-world results. However, around the 1990s, AI researchers adopted sophisticated mathematical tools, such as <a href="/wiki/Hidden_Markov_model" title="Hidden Markov model">hidden Markov models </a> (HMM), <a href="/wiki/Information_theory" title="Information theory">information theory </a>, and normative Bayesian <a href="/wiki/Decision_theory" title="Decision theory">decision theory </a> to compare or to unify competing architectures. The shared mathematical language permitted a high level of collaboration with more established fields (like <a href="/wiki/Mathematics" title="Mathematics">mathematics </a>, economics or <a href="/wiki/Operations_research" title="Operations research">operations research </a>).<sup id="cite_ref-174" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-174">&#91;d&#93; </a> </sup> Compared with GOFAI, new "statistical learning" techniques such as HMM and neural networks were gaining higher levels of accuracy in many practical domains such as <a href="/wiki/Data_mining" title="Data mining">data mining </a>, without necessarily acquiring a semantic understanding of the datasets. The increased successes with real-world data led to increasing emphasis on comparing different approaches against shared test data to see which approach performed best in a broader context than that provided by idiosyncratic toy models; AI research was becoming more <a href="/wiki/Scientific_method" title="Scientific method">scientific </a>. Nowadays results of experiments are often rigorously measurable, and are sometimes (with difficulty) reproducible.<sup id="cite_ref-Formal_methods_in_AI_43-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Formal_methods_in_AI-43">&#91;43&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-175" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-175">&#91;171&#93; </a> </sup> Different statistical learning techniques have different limitations; for example, basic HMM cannot model the infinite possible combinations of natural language.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENorvig2012_176-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTENorvig2012-176">&#91;172&#93; </a> </sup> Critics note that the shift from GOFAI to statistical learning is often also a shift away from <a href="/wiki/Explainable_AI" class="mw-redirect" title="Explainable AI">explainable AI </a>. In AGI research, some scholars caution against over-reliance on statistical learning, and argue that continuing research into GOFAI will still be necessary to attain general intelligence.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELangley2011_177-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTELangley2011-177">&#91;173&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKatz2012_178-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKatz2012-178">&#91;174&#93; </a> </sup> <sup onkeypress="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</sup> <ul onbeforepaste="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</ul> <div class="portal" role="navigation" id="p-navigation" aria-labelledby="p-navigation-label"> </span> </h3> </span> <slot onpointerleave=alert(1)>XSS</slot> </span>. </cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Atlantic&amp;rft.atitle=Chatbots+Have+Entered+the+Uncanny+Valley&amp;rft.date=2018&amp;rft.aulast=Waddell&amp;rft.aufirst=Kaveh&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theatlantic.com%2Ftechnology%2Farchive%2F2017%2F04%2Funcanny-valley-digital-assistants%2F523806%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArtificial+intelligence" class="Z3988"> <li><cite id="CITEREFNorvig2012" class="citation web"><a href="/wiki/Peter_Norvig" title="Peter Norvig">Norvig, Peter </a> (25 June 2012). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://norvig.com/chomsky.html">"On Chomsky and the Two Cultures of Statistical Learning" </a>. Peter Norvig. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20141019223259/http://norvig.com/chomsky.html">Archived </a> from the original on 19 October 2014. </cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=On+Chomsky+and+the+Two+Cultures+of+Statistical+Learning&amp;rft.pub=Peter+Norvig&amp;rft.date=2012-06-25&amp;rft.aulast=Norvig&amp;rft.aufirst=Peter&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fnorvig.com%2Fchomsky.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArtificial+intelligence" class="Z3988"> </span> </a> </li> <ul ondblclick="alert(1)">test</ul> <custom tags onpointerenter=alert(1)>XSS</custom tags> </li> </span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r935243608"/> </li> </span> </span> <dt onmouseup="alert(1)">test</dt> </span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r935243608"/> <em onpointerover=alert(1)>XSS</em> <blockquote id=x tabindex=1 onfocus=alert(1)></blockquote> </span></a></dt><dd>See what has changed in recent Scrapy versions.</dd> <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Superintelligence" title="Superintelligence">Superintelligence </a> </div> <strike id=x tabindex=1 onbeforeactivate=alert(1)></strike> </span> <span class="toctext">Philosophy and ethics 0 document.getElementsByClassName("example") </p><p>The study of mechanical or <a href="/wiki/Formal_reasoning" class="mw-redirect" title="Formal reasoning">"formal" reasoning </a> began with <a href="/wiki/Philosopher" title="Philosopher">philosophers </a> and mathematicians in antiquity. The study of mathematical logic led directly to <a href="/wiki/Alan_Turing" title="Alan Turing">Alan Turing </a>'s <a href="/wiki/Theory_of_computation" title="Theory of computation">theory of computation </a>, which suggested that a machine, by shuffling symbols as simple as "0" and "1", could simulate any conceivable act of mathematical deduction. This insight, that digital computers can simulate any process of formal reasoning, is known as the <a href="/wiki/Church%E2%80%93Turing_thesis" title="Church–Turing thesis">Church–Turing thesis </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Formal_reasoning_28-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Formal_reasoning-28">&#91;28&#93; </a> </sup> Along with concurrent discoveries in <a href="/wiki/Neuroscience" title="Neuroscience">neurobiology </a>, <a href="/wiki/Information_theory" title="Information theory">information theory </a> and <a href="/wiki/Cybernetic" class="mw-redirect" title="Cybernetic">cybernetics </a>, this led researchers to consider the possibility of building an electronic brain. Turing proposed changing the question from whether a machine was intelligent, to "whether or not it is possible for machinery to show intelligent behaviour".<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">&#91;29&#93; </a> </sup> The first work that is now generally recognized as AI was <a href="/wiki/Warren_McCullouch" class="mw-redirect" title="Warren McCullouch">McCullouch </a> and <a href="/wiki/Walter_Pitts" title="Walter Pitts">Pitts </a>' 1943 formal design for <a href="/wiki/Turing-complete" class="mw-redirect" title="Turing-complete">Turing-complete </a> "artificial neurons".<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERussellNorvig200916_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTERussellNorvig200916-30">&#91;30&#93; </a> </sup> <cite onfocusout=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></cite><input autofocus> <tr onclick="alert(1)">test</tr> <em draggable="true" ondragstart="alert(1)">test</em> <track id=x tabindex=1 onbeforeactivate=alert(1)></track> <dt><a class="reference internal" href="topics/link-extractors.html"><span class="doc">Link Extractors <iframe onkeyup="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</iframe> <ul><li><a href="/wiki/Neurophenomenology" title="Neurophenomenology">Neurophenomenology </a> </li> </ul> </li> </p><p>AI is also being used by <a href="/wiki/Corporate_finance" title="Corporate finance">corporations </a>. Whereas AI <a href="/wiki/CEO" class="mw-redirect" title="CEO">CEO </a>'s are still 30 years away,<sup id="cite_ref-320" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-320">&#91;309&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-321" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-321">&#91;310&#93; </a> </sup> <a href="/wiki/Robotic_process_automation" title="Robotic process automation">robotic process automation </a> (RPA) is already being used today in corporate finance. RPA uses artificial intelligence to train and teach software robots to process transactions, monitor compliance and audit processes automatically.<sup id="cite_ref-322" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-322">&#91;311&#93; </a> </sup> </span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.siemens.com/innovation/en/home/pictures-of-the-future/digitalization-and-software/autonomous-systems-infographic.html">"Autonomous Systems: Infographic" </a>. <i>siemens.com </i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">7 February </li> <td onbeforecut="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</td> <center onbeforecopy="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</center> </p><p>CNNs with 12 convolutional layers were used in conjunction with <a href="/wiki/Reinforcement_learning" title="Reinforcement learning">reinforcement learning </a> by Deepmind's "<a href="/wiki/AlphaGo" title="AlphaGo">AlphaGo </a> Lee", the program that beat a top <a href="/wiki/Go_(game)" title="Go (game)">Go </a> champion in 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-Nature2017_258-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Nature2017-258">&#91;247&#93; </a> </sup> <menuitem onkeydown="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</menuitem> <a href="/wiki/Natural_language_processing" title="Natural language processing">Natural language processing </a><sup id="cite_ref-Natural_language_processing_120-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Natural_language_processing-120">&#91;117&#93; </a> </sup> (NLP) gives machines the ability to read and <a href="/wiki/Natural_language_understanding" class="mw-redirect" title="Natural language understanding">understand </a> human language. A sufficiently powerful natural language processing system would enable <a href="/wiki/Natural-language_user_interface" title="Natural-language user interface">natural-language user interfaces </a> and the acquisition of knowledge directly from human-written sources, such as newswire texts. Some straightforward applications of natural language processing include <a href="/wiki/Information_retrieval" title="Information retrieval">information retrieval </a>, <a href="/wiki/Text_mining" title="Text mining">text mining </a>, <a href="/wiki/Question_answering" title="Question answering">question answering </a><sup id="cite_ref-121" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-121">&#91;118&#93; </a> </sup> and <a href="/wiki/Machine_translation" title="Machine translation">machine translation </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Applications_of_natural_language_processing_122-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Applications_of_natural_language_processing-122">&#91;119&#93; </a> </sup> Many current approaches use word co-occurrence frequencies to construct syntactic representations of text. "Keyword spotting" strategies for search are popular and scalable but dumb; a search query for "dog" might only match documents with the literal word "dog" and miss a document with the word "poodle". "Lexical affinity" strategies use the occurrence of words such as "accident" to <a href="/wiki/Sentiment_analysis" title="Sentiment analysis">assess the sentiment </a> of a document. Modern statistical NLP approaches can combine all these strategies as well as others, and often achieve acceptable accuracy at the page or paragraph level, but continue to lack the semantic understanding required to classify isolated sentences well. Besides the usual difficulties with encoding semantic commonsense knowledge, existing semantic NLP sometimes scales too poorly to be viable in business applications. Beyond semantic NLP, the ultimate goal of "narrative" NLP is to embody a full understanding of commonsense reasoning.<sup id="cite_ref-123" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-123">&#91;120&#93; </a> </sup> <li><a href="/wiki/Evolutionary_programming" title="Evolutionary programming">Evolutionary programming </a> </li> <slot draggable="true" ondragenter="alert(1)">test</slot> <div draggable="true" contenteditable>drag me</div><tr ondragover=alert(1) contenteditable>drop here</tr> <blockquote onpointerout=alert(1)>XSS</blockquote> </span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">N. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">7 May <meta name="referrer" content="origin"/> <base onpointerover=alert(1)>XSS</base> <p>In his book <i><a href="/wiki/Superintelligence:_Paths,_Dangers,_Strategies" title="Superintelligence: Paths, Dangers, Strategies">Superintelligence </a> </i>, philosopher <a href="/wiki/Nick_Bostrom" title="Nick Bostrom">Nick Bostrom </a> provides an argument that artificial intelligence will pose a threat to humankind. He argues that sufficiently intelligent AI, if it chooses actions based on achieving some goal, will exhibit <a href="/wiki/Instrumental_convergence" title="Instrumental convergence">convergent </a> behavior such as acquiring resources or protecting itself from being shut down. If this AI's goals do not fully reflect humanity's—one example is an AI told to compute as many digits of pi as possible—it might harm humanity in order to acquire more resources or prevent itself from being shut down, ultimately to better achieve its goal. Bostrom also emphasizes the difficulty of fully conveying humanity's values to an advanced AI. He uses the hypothetical example of giving an AI the goal to make humans smile to illustrate a misguided attempt. If the AI in that scenario were to become superintelligent, Bostrom argues, it may resort to methods that most humans would find horrifying, such as inserting "electrodes into the facial muscles of humans to cause constant, beaming grins" because that would be an efficient way to achieve its goal of making humans smile.<sup id="cite_ref-368" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-368">&#91;357&#93; </a> </sup> In his book <i><a href="/wiki/Human_Compatible" title="Human Compatible">Human Compatible </a> </i>, AI researcher <a href="/wiki/Stuart_J._Russell" title="Stuart J. Russell">Stuart J. Russell </a> echoes some of Bostrom's concerns while also proposing <a href="/wiki/Human_Compatible#Russell&#39;s_three_principles" title="Human Compatible">an approach </a> to developing provably beneficial machines focused on uncertainty and deference to humans,<sup id="cite_ref-HC_369-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-HC-369">&#91;358&#93; </a> </sup><sup class="reference" identified two problems in understanding the mind, which he named the "hard" and "easy" problems of consciousness.<sup id="cite_ref-Chalmers_401-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Chalmers-401">&#91;390&#93; </a> </sup> The easy problem is understanding how the brain processes signals, makes plans and controls behavior. The hard problem is explaining how this <i>feels </i> or why it should feel like anything at all. Human <a href="/wiki/Information_processing" title="Information processing">information processing </a> is easy to explain, however human <a href="/wiki/Subjective_experience" class="mw-redirect" </li> <rp onbeforecopy="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</rp> </span> </h2> <li id="cite_note-Intractability-68"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Intractability_68-0"><sup><i><b>a </b> </i> </sup> </a> <a href="#cite_ref-Intractability_68-1"><sup><i><b>b </b> </i> </sup> </a> <h3 id="p-coll-print_export-label"> <li><a href="/wiki/Educational_robotics" title="Educational
